<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, April 16 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japanese Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori assured visiting
Indonesian President Abdurrahman Wahid on Sunday that Japan has
not altered its policy of supporting Indonesia's reform efforts
despite the recent change in Japan's premiership.
</P>
<P>
Mori told Wahid that Japan will continue to support Indonesia's
economic reconstruction and its efforts to resolve problems over
separatist activities in Aceh and religious strife in the Maluku
Islands, Kyodo news agency quoted a Japanese government official
as saying. (Japan-Indonesia-Reform)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- London would lift the suspension of Northern
Ireland's home-rule government should the Irish Republican Army (
IRA) announce the "war is over" with Britain, the Observer
newspaper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was raised by Britain's Northern Ireland Secretary
Peter Mandelson as part of a new initiative drawn up between
London and Dublin in order to revive the stalled peace process in
the province, according to the paper. (Ulster-IRA-Peace)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian Foreign Ministry on Sunday rejected foreign
interference in the trial on 13 Iranian Jews accused of espionage
for Tehran's arch foes -- the United States and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi said the comments made by some
foreign officials on the judicial process concerning the trial are
"questionable" and will not help the defendants, the Islamic
Republic News Agency reported. (Iran-Jews-Interference)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel will keep on suspending its role in the
five-nation committee monitoring conflicts in south Lebanon,
Israeli military sources said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Israel has to weigh its membership in the committee as long as
Lebanese "terrorist organizations" continue violating the
understandings, a statement issued by Israel Defense Forces (IDF)
said. (Israel-South Lebanon)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HARARE -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe said Sunday that
he will not order the war veterans to withdraw from white farms
they have been occupying.
</P>
<P>
"All the British newspapers were expecting me to order the war
veterans to leave the farms. I will not say that and I will not do
that. Why should they leave the land now. They should wait for
the law to be implemented and only then," Mugabe said to a
resounding applause. (Zimbabwe-President-Land)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Transportation Minister Yitzhak Mordechai
is facing indictment on three counts of sexual assault and sexual
harassment based on complaints filed by three women, police
spokeswoman said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The police investigation team for the case ended their probe
Sunday afternoon and turned the findings to the State Attorney's
Office, saying that they collected enough evidence to support
their recommendations to charge Mordechai with indecent sexual
acts with force. (Israel-Minister-Harassment 1st lead )
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Lebanese President Emile Lahoud ended his two-
day visit to Saudi Arabia Sunday, securing Saudi support in his
country's struggle to halt Israel's continuous attacks on Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud, who arrived in the Gulf kingdom Saturday on the first
leg of his seven-nation tour of Arab states and Iran, held talks
late Saturday with Saudi King Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz, and Crown
Prince and Deputy Prime Minister Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz. (
Lebanon-Saudi Arabia) 
</P>
</TEXT>
