<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syria Never Gives Up Inch of Territories: Vice President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUSM, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Third Vice President
Mohammed Zouhair Musharaqah vowed Monday that his country would
never give up any inch of its territories or compromise its rights
and sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
The vow was made during the celebrations held by the Damascus
Committee of the ruling Arab Socialist Baathist Party at the
Damascus University to mark the 54th anniversary of Syrian
Liberation.
</P>
<P>
On April 17, 1946, the last soldier of the French occupation
forces left Syria, marking Syria's independence from French
colonial rule.
</P>
<P>
"The peace that is based on securing gains for the aggressor can
not be considered peace, it is rather a surrender that can lead to
a future struggle," Musharaqah said, noting that "many historical
facts testify to that."
</P>
<P>
"Peace must return the rights to their legitimate owners. On top
of such rights are the rights to land, sovereignty and security,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
"The party that insists on carving up a piece of land, usurping
part of the rights, and imposing hegemony, insists in fact on
achieving its hostile targets," the Syrian leader pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Israeli peace talks, resumed last December after a
nearly-four-year break, have been stalled again since January.
Syria
demanded a written commitment from Israel to fully returning the
Israeli-occupied Golan Heights which it captured from Syria in the
1967 Middle East war. Israel refused to do so, demanding that
security arrangements and normalization of bilateral ties be
discussed first.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also disputed over the Tiberias Lake, or Sea of
Galilee. Syria insists on restoring its sovereignty over the
northeastern bank of the lake, while Israel claims full sovereignty
over the lake.
</P>
<P>
There are some proposals to break the deadlock such as launching
joint tourist projects by Syria and Israel or declaring the lake as
an international natural conservation.
</P>
<P>
Syria will remain committed to the peace process and adhere to
the principles and references on which the process was based,
Musharaqah added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
