<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Deficit in Palestine Up To 436 Million Cubic Meters: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian Water Department
(PWD) said in a report issued here on Monday that the water deficit
in Palestine reaches 436 million cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
While the water demand in Palestine amounts to 740 million cubic
meters, the supply stands at 257 million only, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The only way to meet the deficit is to restore all the rights of
the Palestinians to water resources, according to Deputy Chief of
the PWD Fadl Kaoush.
</P>
<P>
Such resources include the surface and subterranean water inside
the West Bank and Gaza Strip and the Jordan River which is an
international basin, Kaoush explained.
</P>
<P>
Under the interim accords between the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) and Israel, the water quota of Palestinians were
estimated between 70 and 80 million cubic meters a year and later
on emergency quota was set at 28.6 million cubic meters, he added.
</P>
<P>
The water reserve in the West Bank exceeds 800 million cubic
meters including 600 million cubic meters of subterranean water
while the water reserve in Gaza Strip amounts to 100 million cubic
meters. The figures could meet the water demand of the three
million Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
However, the Israeli population estimated at five million people
and the 179,000 Jewish settlers consume up to 80 percent of the
Palestinian water supply.
</P>
<P>
The redistribution of water resources is one of the thorny
issues in the final status talks between the PNA and Israel that
started half a year ago without making any tangible progress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
