<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: New Rwandan President-Elect Paul Kagame </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Major General Paul Kagame was
elected the President of Rwanda on Monday for the remaining three
years of the transitional period and will take office on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Kagame was born in a rich Tutsi family in October 1957 in
Gitarama Prefecture in central Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
He fled with parents to Uganda in the pre-independence upheaval
and turmoil that beset Rwanda in 1960.
</P>
<P>
He lived and studied in primary and secondary schools in Uganda
in the sixties and seventies.
</P>
<P>
He is a graduate of Fort Lavenworth Military School in Kansas,
the United States, where he attended a staff and command course.
</P>
<P>
In 1979 he commenced his military career with the Uganda
National Liberation Army to fight against Idi Amin.
</P>
<P>
From 1986 to 1990 he served as a senior army officer in the
Ugandan Army until he returned to his motherland.
</P>
<P>
He took over command of the Tutsi-dominated Rwanda Patriotic
Front (RPF) and led it to a decisive victory in July 1994
following the genocide which left at least 500,000 Tutsis and
moderate Hutus dead.
</P>
<P>
Two weeks later he was appointed Minister of Defence and Vice
President.
</P>
<P>
In 1998 he was elected chairman of the RPF.
</P>
<P>
On March 27 this year, he was appointed interim President by
the Supreme Court following the resignation of President Pasteur
Bizimungu.
</P>
<P>
On April 1, he was unanimously nominated as presidential
candidate by the 75-member RPF Political Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Paul Kagame is married to Janet, and they have four children.
He is a keen tennis player and an ardent football fan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000417.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Kill 2 Million People in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kampala, April 17 (Xinhua) -- About two million Ugandans have
been confirmed dead as a result of HIV/AIDS, one of the key
killer diseases in this east African country.
</P>
<P>
Uganda AIDS Commission (UAC) Director Kihumuro Apuuli made the
 revelation when meeting with an Indian delegation of AIDS control
here Monday, Radio Uganda reported.
</P>
<P>
About 500,000 people in the country have been affected with the
epidemic,
</P>
<P>
Apuuli said, adding that at least 1.9 million children have been
orphaned due to wide-spread HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The first case of AIDS was reported in Uganda in 1982. AIDS
prevalence rate was as high as over 30 percent in late 1980s and
early 1990s. It has dropped to 10 percent due to the government's
increasing efforts against the disease and great enhancement of
people's awareness. Uganda is the only African country where AIDS
prevalence rate is dropping.
</P>
<P>
The Indian 13-member delegation is here on one-week visit to
learn from the Ugandan experience in AIDS control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000417.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda to Enhance Rural Electricity Coverage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kampala, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government has vowed
to increase the rural electricity coverage in the country from
current one percent to 10 percent in the next 10 years, a senior
government official has said.
</P>
<P>
Syda Bumba, minister of energy and mineral development, made
the revelation at the handover ceremony of a Japan-aided power
station in Mukono district, 25 km east of the capital city
Kampala, on Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is the policy of the government to provide
sustainable and coordinative rural electrification strategies for
the whole country, according to a Radio Uganda report.
</P>
<P>
The rural electrification project was constructed by the Japan
 International Cooperation Agency at a cost of 10 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan annual electricity production stands at 180
megawatts against a demand of 260 megawatts. The national
electricity coverage is now five percent, over 80 percent of
which is in the three main cities of Kampala, Entebbe and Jinja.
</P>
</TEXT>
