<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Substantive Talks Called for to Solve Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The leaders of the Greek and
Turkish Cypriot communities on the divided Cyprus island must hold
substantive talks based on U.N. resolutions to solve the Cyprus
issue, leaders of two parties on the Cyprus island appealed on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was made at a meeting between Cyprus' left-wing AKEL
party General Secretary Demetris Christofias and Turkish Cypriot
Patriotic Unity Movement leader Izzet Izcan, the Cyprus News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that the only way that can reunite the country is
through a federation formula.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities since 1974 when Turkey invaded and occupied the
northern third of the island in the wake of a failed coup seeking
union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for years to bring the two sides back
together in a bizonal, bicommunal federation formula but all
efforts have failed so far.
</P>
<P>
Two rounds of U.N.-sponsored proximity talks have been held
between the two sides to lay the ground for substantive
negotiations which may lead to a comprehensive settlement of the
Cyprus issue. The third round of talks are due to begin on May 23
in New York.
</P>
<P>
Izcan said that his Movement and AKEL will soon announce events
organized by the two parties, which "work for the unity of the
country, for democracy, human rights and a solution" to the Cyprus
issue.
</P>
<P>
He said that the federal formula "is the only solution which can
reunite the country, which can be accepted by international law and
which is based on U.N. resolutions and the 1977 and 1979 high level
agreements" by the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Izcan said that "the majority of the Turkish Cypriots are in
favor of a federal solution" and stressed the need for
rapprochement between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Christofias said that "good will" is needed on both sides to
solve the Cyprus issue and noted that "a substantive dialogue must
take place."
</P>
<P>
He added that both sides must grasp the opportunities available
toward this end and that every form of contact between the two
sides contributes to this goal.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from both AKEL and the Patriotic Unity Movement
attended a Greek and Turkish Cypriot political parties' meeting in
February at the U.N.-controlled buffer zone in Nicosia, which was
the first official contact between the two sides since 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
