<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan: Consensus On Precise, Specific Aims of Sanctions Must be Achieved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 17 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Monday said that it is not enough to make sanctions
"smart", and the challenge is to achieve consensus about the
precise and specific aims of the sanctions, adjust the instruments
accordingly and then provide the necessary means.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the seminar on sanctions by the International Peace
Academy, Annan said "we recognize the importance of sanctions as a
way of compelling compliance with the will of the international
community, we also recognized that sanctions remain a blunt
instrument, which hurt large numbers of people who are not their
primary targets,"
</P>
<P>
"Sanctions need refining if they are to be seen as more than a
figleaf in the future," the U.N. chief said.
</P>
<P>
The Secretariat has undertaken a review of lessons learned from
recent sanctions regimes, focusing in particular on the need to
protect vulnerable communities from the effects of sanctions,
while improving the targeting of elites, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
The review has also illustrated the need for credible
monitoring mechanisms for sanctions regimes, and the importance of
having necessary resources to effectively administer them, Annan
said.
</P>
<P>
"We at the United Nations and in the international community
at large need to make greater efforts to ensure that when
sanctions are imposed against a Member State, we are able to make
a clear and convincing case for their necessity and their ultimate
aim," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is clear that the last decades' proliferation of sanctions
regimes and the diverse range of purposes for which they were
employed have imposed on the international community a heavy
obligation to ensure that this instrument is employed with great
care and a clear understanding of its effects, both intended and
unintended," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Annan expressed the hope the Security Council would further
take a broader look at the issuers which arise in respect of
sanctions regimes and that it would take into account recent Swiss
and German studies aimed at improving targeted financial sanctions
and arms embargoes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
