<HEADLINE> Canada's Inflation Rises to 3 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Canada's annual inflation rate
rose to 3 percent in March, compared with 2.7 percent recorded for
the previous month, Statistics Canada reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
On a month-to-month basis, the inflation jump reached 0.7
percent between February and March, the largest since January 1991.
</P>
<P>
More than half that increase was due to gasoline prices, which
accounted for 57 percent of the monthly rise.
</P>
<P>
Gasoline prices rose 8.8 percent in March and, on an annual
basis, were 38 percent higher than that of last year.
</P>
<P>
The annual core rate, excluding food and energy, was 1.4
percent from February's 1.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Canada aims to keep inflation between one and three
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
