<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council to Debate on Sanctions Regimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Security Council is scheduled Monday afternoon to hold an open
debate on the sanction regimes in a bid to make them more
effective.
</P>
<P>
Imposing sanctions is regarded as a way of compelling
compliance with the will of the international community. It also
remains a blunt instrument which hurt large numbers of people who
are not their primary targets.
</P>
<P>
Under Article 41 of the U.N. Charter, the United Nations
Security Council may call upon Member States to apply measures not
involving the use of armed force in order to maintain or restore
international peace and security. Such measures are commonly
referred to as sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council has imposed sanctions in fourteen cases:
Afghanistan, Angola, Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, Haiti, Iraq,
Liberia, Libya, Rwanda, Sierra Leone, Somalia, South Africa,
Southern Rhodesia, Sudan and former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
In the case of Haiti, South Africa, Southern Rhodesia and
former Yugoslavia, sanctions have been fully lifted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000417.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Report: World Ecosystems Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The decline is due to rising resource demands which have
devastating implications for human development and the welfare of
all species, the U.N. Development Program (UNDP) and other U.N.
agencies said in an advance press release on their forthcoming
report.
</P>
<P>
Half of the world's wetlands were lost last century and logging
and conversion have shrunk the world's forests by as much as half,
according to the report to be published in September.
</P>
<P>
The report, the Guide to the World Resources 2000-2001: People
and Ecosystems: The Fraying Web of Life, has also found:
</P>
<P>
the global economy has tripled in size while population has
grown by 30 percent to six billion people in the last two decades;
</P>
<P>
some 9 percent of the world's tree species are at risk of
extinction;
</P>
<P>
fishing fleets are 40 percent larger than the ocean can sustain;
</P>
<P>
nearly 70 percent of the world's major marine fish stocks are
overfished or are being fished at their biological limit;
</P>
<P>
soil degradation has affected two-thirds of the world's
agricultural lands in the last 50 years;
</P>
<P>
some 30 percent of the world's original forests have been
converted to agriculture.
</P>
<P>
An important conclusion the U.N. agencies have drawn is that
there is a lack of the knowledge needed to properly determine
ecosystems conditions on a global, regional and local scale.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
