<HEADLINE> Italian President Refuses D'Alema's Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The protocol used meant that Ciampi did not accept D'Alema's
resignation on the grounds that Parliament was the proper forum to
verify whether he was still in a position to govern, a spokesman
for the presidential Quirinale Palace explained.
</P>
<P>
The opposition Bloc center-right won control of eight Italian
regions in the regional election held Sunday, leaving the center-
left with seven of the nine they won at last vote in 1995.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with the head of state, D'Alema told the press
that he left it would be "a serious mistake" to dissolve
parliament in the near future.
</P>
<P>
"A referendum has been scheduled, one admitted by the
Constitutional Court, which involves the electoral law," the
premier explained, "My opinion is that it is the duty of
Parliament to reform the electoral law and give (Italy) a system
which guarantees greater stability and authority to the government
".
</P>
<P>
In explaining his decision to offer his resignation, D'Alema
told the press "I believe it is right, out of political
correctness and certainly not institutional duty, to recognize the
result of the hard political confrontation in the regional
elections which saw the success of the opposition which had, from
the beginning, demanded the resignation of the government".
</P>
<P>
Turning his attention to the decision which Parliament will
make, D'Alema concluded "it will be my responsibility to accept it
".
</P>
</TEXT>
