<HEADLINE> Greek Stocks Suffer Biggest Drop in History  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Affected by the declining New
York Stock Exchange and other international stock markets, equity
prices in Greece suffered their biggest drop ever on the Athens
Stock Exchange (ASE) Monday.
</P>
<P>
The ASE general index plunged 9.17 percent to 4,064.85 points,
and the FTSE/ASE 20 index ended at 2,301.02 points, down 9.16
percent.
</P>
<P>
Turnover was a moderate 145 billion drachmas (about 416
million U.S. dollars) and decliners led advancers by 332 to two
with another two issues unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The leasing and construction sectors led the falling stock
market by dropping 9.95 percent and 9.96 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
On March 14, the Greek stocks suffered a 6.6 percent drop and
a 5.29 percent last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Monday's ASE losses, Greek government spokesman
Dimitris Reppas said that there was a crisis in the international
stock market and the ASE was impossible to be unaffected.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Greek economic prospects were positive and
justified a medium-and long-term advance in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman added that the firm position of the Greek
government was to shield the stock market and undertake specific
initiatives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
