<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean President Meets White Farmers Over Farm Invasions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
on Monday met the leaders of white commercial farmers to discuss
the occupation of about 1,000 farms by the black war veterans.
</P>
<P>
President of the Commercial Farmers' Union Tim Henwood and
President of Zimbabwe Tobacco Association Richard Tate held a
two-hour meeting with Mugabe, which they described as fruitful and
"very good", the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, the first since the war veterans invaded
white-owned farms almost two months ago, came a day after Mugabe
said he would not order the war veterans to withdraw from the
occupied farms.
</P>
<P>
There might be another meeting on Tuesday, Independence Day, to
further discuss the land issue.
</P>
<P>
The commercial farmers appealed to the President to help
restore the situation to normal, saying that this could only
happen with the withdrawal of the war veterans from the occupied
farms.
</P>
<P>
"We discussed the situation, which includes the land issue and
the disruption to agriculture. We appealed to the President to
restore things to normal. We were given an assurance by the
President. We had a very good discussion," Henwood said.
</P>
<P>
He said the commercial farmers reaffirmed their support for the
land redistribution program.
</P>
<P>
Tate said they made suggestions to the President on the land
redistribution process, but could not be drawn to reveal the
proposals.
</P>
<P>
"There is a lot of land available. We made suggestions and we
will let the President announce them. Everyone must contribute
and we should all work together," he said.
</P>
<P>
Henwood pointed out that the land issue was a Zimbabwean
problem, which needed a Zimbabwean solution.
</P>
<P>
He dismissed offers by the British to evacuate the white
commercial farmers.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 white-owned commercial farms have been invaded
by former freedom fighters, saying they have lost patience at the
pace at which the government is implementing its land
redistribution program.
</P>
<P>
The war veterans of the 1970s liberation struggle have vowed to
remain on the farms, despite the passing of an amendment to the
constitution which allows the government to acquire land without
compensation.
</P>
<P>
Henwood has in the past said the invasions could cost the
country millions of dollars, including the much-needed foreign
currency.
</P>
<P>
He said that they appealed to the President to intervene in
Macheke where a white commercial farmer was shot dead allegedly by
war veterans.  
</P>
</TEXT>
