<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Delays Opening of Tobacco Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's tobacco auction floors,
one of the world's main tobacco markets, are now likely to open
sometime in May, instead of the scheduled April 26, due to the
disruptions at some commercial farms by war veterans, an official
said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
President of the Zimbabwe Tobacco Association Richard Tate told
 reporters after meeting President Robert Mugabe that because of
the farm invasions, the opening of the auction floors would have
to be delayed further to May.
</P>
<P>
He dispelled rumors that the tobacco farmers were threatening
to withhold the crop until the Zimbabwean dollar devalues further.
</P>
<P>
He said because of the farm invasions, about 70 farms had been
deserted.
</P>
<P>
About 1,000 commercial farms have been invaded by the war
veterans countrywide since February.
</P>
<P>
Farmers are expecting to sell 220 million kilograms of
flue-cured tobacco, well above last year's 196 million kilograms.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco is the country's biggest foreign currency earner.
</P>
<P>
Tate said they also discussed a further devaluation of the
dollar with the President.
</P>
<P>
He did not give a preferred rate, but some commercial farmers
have suggested that to break even, the Zimbabwean dollar should
devalue to 78 against the U.S. dollar from 38.
</P>
<P>
While waiting for the commercial farmers, President Mugabe
indicated to acting Agriculture Minister Joyce Mujuru that the
government would not agree to devalue the dollar further.
</P>
<P>
Governor of the Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe Leonard Tsumba has
already dismissed possibilities of a further devaluation.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe is grappling with an unsteady currency which fell by
over 50 percent last year and is only being held stable by an
informal control by the banks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
