<HEADLINE> Kagame Elected Rwandan President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Major General Paul Kagame was
elected the fifth Rwandan president on Monday by 81 votes of 86
members of cabinet and parliament, Rwanda News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The 65 Members of Parliament and 21 Cabinet members cast a
secret ballot in a swift presidential election, with the other
candidate Charles Murigande getting five votes.
</P>
<P>
Vincent Biruta, the Speaker, announced that Paul Kagame had
been elected president for the remaining three years of
transitional period.
</P>
<P>
"I accept and appreciate the heavy onus of the Presidency for
the remaining difficult term of the transitional period, but I
count on your support," Kagame said after the voting.
</P>
<P>
He promised to deliver the badly needed unity, justice and
development to the Rwandans.
</P>
<P>
Kagame is to be sworn in on Saturday, the Speaker said.
</P>
<P>
"Soon after the elections, the results are to be channelled
through the supreme court, in accordance with Article 48, of the
Arusha Peace accord," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kagame assumed the interim president after Pasteur Bizimungu
resigned from the presidency on March 23.
</P>
<P>
Kagame, former vice president and defence minister, was
nominated one of the two presidential candidates by the ruling
Rwandan Patriotic Front earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Paul Kagame, born in Gitarama in central Rwanda in October
1957, was a career soldier and a senior military officer in the
Uganda Army before triumphantly returning to quell the 1994
genocide in Rwanda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
