<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Washington Summit Substantial, Basic in Pushing Peace Process: Arafat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
asserted here Monday that his upcoming summit meeting with U.S.
President Bill Clinton in Washington is a "substantial and basic
point" in pushing forward the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat made the remarks following his meeting with visiting
Omani Minister of State for Foreign Affairs Yousef Bin Alawi Bin
Abdullah.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and Clinton are due to meet in Washington on April 20 in
an effort to advance the ongoing Israeli-Palestinian talks at the
Bolling Air Base near Washington.
</P>
<P>
The two sides are striving hard to draft a framework agreement
by May for a final peace treaty by September.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Clinton himself supervised the signing of
the Oslo and Wye River agreements by the Palestinian and Israeli
sides, and he also supervised the recent peace march by sending
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright to attend the signing
ceremony for the Sharm el Sheikh memorandum on behalf of him last
September.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said his meeting with Clinton comes within this movement,
noting that Clinton demanded Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak make
progress on negotiations with the Palestinians, the Syrians and the
Lebanese.
</P>
<P>
Arafat also stressed that he supports such a positive movement
and trend since it is consistent with what has been agreed in the
Madrid peace conference in 1991, which was designed for bringing
about a comprehensive and lasting peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader confirmed that "the independent state
will be set up this year."
</P>
<P>
On his part, Yousef said he conveyed a message to Arafat from
Omani Sultan Qaboos Bin Said which expressed the Omani people's
support to the Palestinians and their just cause at "this crucial
stage."
</P>
<P>
The minister said he discussed with Arafat the latest
developments of the peace process, and the bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his hope that the coordinated efforts being exerted
by the Arab countries will be positive for the sake of Arab nations
and the Palestinian cause.
</P>
<P>
The Omani minister indicated that his country and the
Palestinian leadership support the holding of an Arab summit in the
very near future.
</P>
<P>
Yousef is here on a working visit to Palestine as part of a
Middle East trip which has also taken him to Egypt.
</P>
<P>
While in Cairo, he stressed on the need to hold an Arab summit
to discuss the peace process, especially the suspended Syrian-
Israeli talks.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Israeli talks, resumed last December after a nearly-
four-year break, have been stalled again since January. Syria
demanded a written commitment from Israel to fully returning the
Israeli-occupied Golan Heights which it captured from Syria in the
1967 Middle East war. Israel refused to do so, demanding that
security arrangements and normalization of bilateral ties be
discussed first.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Arafat's advisor Nabil Abu Redina said Arafat's
meeting with Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein, slated for
Monday, has been postponed to Tuesday or until Arafat returns from
Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
