<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Installs First Barge Mounted Power Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's first ever barge
mounted thermal power plant was installed Monday at the Colombo
port to add 60 megawatts of power to the national grid.
</P>
<P>
"Testing and commissioning will commence in May and completion
of the plant is scheduled by end of June. The commercial operation
will start from the beginning of July 2000," said Akitsu Odagaki,
chairman of Colombo Power (Pvt) Ltd. which installed the plant.
</P>
<P>
He told a new conference here on Monday evening that the plant
will be owned, operated and maintained by the company until the
year 2015 under a power purchase agreement signed in February 1999
with Sri Lanka's Ceylon Electricity Board.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of the Ministry of Irrigation and Power Jaliya
Medagama said the plant is part of the government's efforts to
encourage private sector's participation into power sector.
</P>
<P>
He said Sri Lanka aims to attract 2.5 billion U.S. dollars
during the next seven years in the power sector in a bid to double
electric energy production.
</P>
<P>
Medagama said the country will rely more on thermal power plant
in the future in order to provide electricity to 47 percent of Sri
Lanka's 19 million population who still have no access to
electricity.
</P>
<P>
The floating plant, which costs around 72 million dollars, was
constructed in Japan on a Build, Own and Operate (BOO) basis by
Colombo Power (Pvt) Ltd., a joint company equally owned by two
Japanese firms, Mitsui Engineering and Shipbuilding Company and
Kawasho Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The plant, brought to Sri Lanka by a massive ship last weekend
and anchored five kilometers away in the deep seas in the outer
harbor of the Colombo port, was taken out of the ship and towed by
tugs into the area in which it was installed at the Colombo port
Monday morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
