<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Urges Developed Countries to Open Markets to Developing Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Developing countries are by and large in the process of
fulfilling their obligations in the agreements concluded in the
Uruguay Round, but developed countries have failed to fully
implement their part specified in the Uruguay Round negotiations
with regard to further opening their markets," said Jin Liqun,
vice minister of finance of China, at the 61th meeting of the
Development Committee, the policy-setting group for the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
China supports the World Bank's efforts in urging developed
countries to pen their markets, Jin said, adding that it is
unreasonable for the developed countries to apply "double
standards" on market access.
</P>
<P>
"While urging developing countries to open those markets where
developed countries enjoy dominating advantages, developed
countries are protecting those of their own domestic industries
where they have long lost comparative advantages, and the barriers
against products of such industries from developing countries
remain high," he said.
</P>
<P>
Such "double standards," Jin added, is harmful not only to
developing countries, but also to the long-term interests of
developed countries themselves.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese official said for quite a long time, developing
countries have not been successfully integrated into the world
trading system. The primary reason for this failure, he said, is
that under the current system developing countries have not been
in an equal position vis-a-vis their trade partners from developed
countries.
</P>
<P>
Jin called on international development institutions to help
developing countries explore how to get equal opportunities and
benefits from trade liberalization.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the poverty reduction issue, Jin said the World
Bank must have a long-term commitment, and stable and continued
policies would be very important to the effectiveness and
efficiency of poverty reduction.
</P>
<P>
The most efficient way to reduce poverty has proved to be
through promotion of economic growth and improvement of income
distribution, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"The past experience has long proved that the World Bank's
comparative advantage still lies in its strength of providing
financial resources and technical assistance to promote economic
growth in developing countries, for the purpose of poverty
reduction," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese vice minister stressed that developed countries
should take concrete measures to reverse the declining trend of
international official assistance and major developed countries
should increase their official development assistance as soon as
possible to reach 0.7 percent of gross domestic product (GDP), a
target set by the United Nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
