<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Notifies U.N. of Withdrawal from Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"The Government of Israel indicates it will cooperate fully
with the United Nations in the implementation of its decision,"
said a statement issued Monday by Annan's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the U.N. chief is studying the implications
of this decision and he is notifying the Security Council of the
contents of the letter dated April 16 from Israeli Foreign
Minister David Levy.
</P>
<P>
Annan will consult with the parties and other concerned
governments in the region and more widely, said the spokesman,
adding that contingency planning in the Secretariat is already
underway.
</P>
<P>
Lancry told reporters later that the withdrawal would be
completed "in one phase" by July 7, 2000.
</P>
<P>
He said the pull-out will be in full accordance with Security
Council resolutions 425 and 426 (1978).
</P>
<P>
The resolutions, calling for immediate cease of Israeli
military action against Lebanese territorial integrity and
withdrawal of Israeli forces from all Lebanese territory, were
adopted after Israel's incursion into southern Lebanon against
Palestinian guerrillas in 1978.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has since deployed a 4,500 member peacekeeping force
in southern Lebanon. The Security Council is expected to discuss
the future of the force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
