<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Residents in Japan Protest Ishihara's Remarks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Three groups of foreign residents
in Kobe, southwestern Japan, on Monday jointly sent a letter to
Tokyo Governor Shintaro Ishihara, protesting against his recent
discriminatory remarks against foreigners living in Japan, Kyodo
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Nationalist Ishihara told members of Japan's Ground Self-
Defense Force on April 9 that Japanese troops should be prepared
for riots by foreigners after a major earthquake in Japan.
</P>
<P>
Ishihara's remarks "were unforgivable as it is a serious
challenge to people who hope for peace and friendship," the letter
said.
</P>
<P>
The three groups are the general association of overseas
Chinese in Kobe, the Hyogo Prefecture headquarters of the Korean
Residents Union in Japan (Mindan) and the Hyogo prefectural
chapter of the General Association of Korean Residents in Japan (
Chongryun).
</P>
<P>
Citing the January 1995 earthquake that devastated Kobe and
adjacent cities, the letter said foreign residents were involved
in helping out each other during the disaster.
</P>
<P>
The letter strongly demanded that Ishihara retract his remarks
and change his discriminatory views against non-Japanese groups.
</P>
<P>
"The three groups have been making efforts to live together
with the Japanese people. We feel indescribable indignation
against the remarks," said Rin Doshun, president of the Chinese
association.
</P>
<P>
"We feel the past five years of efforts we've been making after
the earthquake has been wasted," said Kim Hyo, deputy chief of
Mindan's Hyogo prefectural headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Li Mun I, chief of Chongryun's Hyogo prefectural chapter, said,
"The remarks were unforgivable for all Koreans in Japan."
</P>
<P>
On April 9, Ishihara said: "Atrocious crimes have been
committed again and again by 'sangokujin' and other foreigners who
have illegally entered Japan. We can expect them to riot in the
event of a disastrous earthquake."
</P>
<P>
"Sangokujin" literally means "people from third countries." The
term gained currency after World War II for referring to people
from the former Japanese colonies in Taiwan and the Korean
Peninsula. It is now widely regarded as a derogatory term.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
