<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Cabinet to Block Freeing Lebanese Detainees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak will convene a special cabinet session on Tuesday to discuss
the way to block the release of 13 Lebanese administrative
detainees now in custody in Israel.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was issued Monday afternoon by Barak's office
after Israel's Supreme Court rejected the appeal against the
release earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
The ruling once seemed to clear the way for the transfer of
these detainees to the International Red Cross organization in
south Lebanon, which was originally due to take place on Monday.
</P>
<P>
But now there will be no new date set for the release before the
cabinet session.
</P>
<P>
Barak's statement said the decision to call a cabinet meeting
was reached after a consultation with Justice Minister Yossi
Beilin, Interior Minister Natan Sharansky, Knesset (parliament)
Speaker Avraham Burg, Attorney-General Elyakim Rubinstein and
defense establishment officials.
</P>
<P>
It also stated that Barak is leaning toward supporting
legislation that would authorize the executive branch, rather than
the judicial branch, to be responsible for determining the holding
of "enemy fighters" for a period of time for the purpose of
redeeming Israeli missing serviceman.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the speaker informed Barak that the Knesset, which is
currently in recess for the Jewish Passover Holiday, will convene
in special session on Tuesday to facilitate the discussion and the
passing of legislation regarding the Lebanese detainees.
</P>
<P>
Israel's prison authority announced last Wednesday that the 13
hostages would be set free following a ruling by the Supreme Court,
which ordered immediately release of eight of them because they
have been illegally kept for years as bargaining chips for missing
Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The family of Israel Air Force navigator Ron Arad, the most
famous among the Israeli soldiers missing in Lebanon since 14 years
ago, submitted a petition on Sunday to block the planned transfer.
</P>
<P>
However, the court upheld its ruling on Monday, saying Israeli
law does not give the defense ministry the authority to hold these
Lebanese citizens in administrative detention as they are not
presenting threats to Israel's security.
</P>
<P>
All these Lebanese hostages are used by Israel as bargaining
cards for information or return of missing Israeli servicemen. Most
of them were detained without trial for over a decade.
</P>
<P>
Since the Supreme Court ruling was announced, senior members of
the defense and judicial establishment have put forward proposals
to explore the possibility of legal ways to bypass it.
</P>
<P>
They are aiming at a law that will justify detaining citizens of
an enemy country as prisoner of wars for the duration of the
conflict, in accordance with the international law.
</P>
<P>
The opposition Likud party and the ultraorthodox religious Shas
party, which hold 19 and 17 crucial seats in the 120-member Knesset
respectively, have already announced they will vote in favor of
such a legislation.
</P>
<P>
However, Public Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami had told Israel
Radio that the court's "brave" decision to release the 13 prisoners
should be upheld, adding that keeping these hostages would not
bring back Israel's missing soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Arab Knesset Member Ahmed Tibi also condemned talks of a bypass
law, arguing that the state does not have a "moral right" to demand
the release of Jews imprisoned in Iran when it now tries to deprive
the Lebanese citizens of their basic rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
