<HEADLINE> U.S. Congressman Regrets For Iraq's Humanitarian Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Democratic Party Congressman
Tony Hall said here on Monday that he feels regret for the "
miserable" humanitarian situation in Iraq, which has been under
sweeping U.N. sanctions since its 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Hall made the remarks while visiting a hospital in Mansour
district of the Iraqi capital, the Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The director of the hospital briefed Hall on the dilapidated
conditions of the hospital, where many patients can not get timely
treatment because of the dire dearth of medicine and medical
equipments.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Hall held talks with Iraqi Health Minister
Umid Medhat Mubarak, who elaborated Hall on Iraq's present
humanitarian situation characterized by mounting mortality rates
and increasing occurrences of cancer and infectious diseases, the
INA said.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Mubarak stressed that the U.S. and British
delegates at the U.N. Sanctions Committee put on hold contracts
Iraq signed with foreign countries within the framework of the U.N.
oil-for-food program to buy humanitarian goods such as food and
medicine.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has repeatedly accused the United States and Britain of
deliberately impeding the implementation of the United Nations oil-
for-food deal, worsening the humanitarian crisis in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has claimed that over 1.5 million people, mostly children
and the elderly, have died as a direct result of the decade-long
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Hall arrived here Sunday evening by land from the Jordanian
capital of Amman.
</P>
<P>
Upon arrival, Hall said his visit to Iraq, the first by an
American congressmen since the 1991 Gulf War which ended Iraq's
months-long occupation of Kuwait, is not political but
humanitarian.
</P>
<P>
During his four-day visit, Hall will visit schools, hospitals
and other facilities in Baghdad and the southern part of Iraq.
</P>
</TEXT>
