<HEADLINE> Britain, India to Pursue Dialogue on Nuclear Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The British foreign secretary, who is on a four-day visit to
India, told a joint press conference that officials from both
sides would meet soon to pursue a formal bilateral dialogue on non-
proliferation and disarmament.
</P>
<P>
He also declared that Britain saw India as a "natural contender
" for permanent membership of the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Reflecting a wide convergence of views on almost all issues,
Cook said Britain and India were "natural partners" who should
base their new partnership on the foundations of being two
modernizing countries."
</P>
<P>
He announced that Britain would be opening two new trade
offices in India in Ahmedabad and Hyderabad and planned to
increase development aid to India from 100 million to 150 million
pounds (about 156 million to 234 million U.S. dollars) per year
over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
Labeling both Britain and India as leading nations in
information technologies and software exports, the British Foreign
Secretary said both the governments are committed to keeping the
countries at the front of the knowledge-based global economy.
</P>
<P>
On the Kashmir issue, he said that sanctity of the Line of
Control (LoC) in Jammu and Kashmir should be respected and called
for an end to violence in Jammu and Kashmir and said the only way
forward was through dialogue and creating "positive political
conditions" in the region.
</P>
<P>
Stating "serious dialogue required real restraint," Cook said
violence could only make problems worse.
</P>
<P>
He said restraint and confidence building measures were
required to reduce tension in the area.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Indian External Affairs Minister Jaswant Singh said
he had held detailed bilateral talks with Cook and the talks were
"very constructive."
</P>
<P>
He said that the two sides had taken a decision to revive Indo-
U.K. Defense Consultative Group and that its fifth meeting would
be held in August.
</P>
<P>
He also indicated that Prime Minister A.B. Vajpayee had
extended an invitation to his British counterpart Tony Blair to
visit India. "We look forward to an early visit. The exact dates
will be decided soon," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
