<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Govt Silent over Power Bill Bribe Try </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Presidential Palace
Monday distanced itself from the alleged bribery of congressmen in
the House of Representatives, as Press Secretary Ricardo Puno
denied Palace involvement.
</P>
<P>
Noting the separation of the executive branch from the
legislature,Puno told reporters that the president's office had no
knowledge of the alleged bribery of solons with half a million
pesos (12,500 U.S.dollars) each for passing the Omnibus Power Bill
on April 12.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the incident, the executive branch had told the
congress to prioritize the bill's passage, due to the insistence
of the country's overseas financial donors like the Asian
Development Bank and the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
Two solons claimed on Sunday that they were each given 500,000
pesos after a marathon House session last week. The session was
meant to pass the power bill before the legislature's Holy Week
recess late April.
</P>
<P>
The said bill mandates the sale of the National Power
Corporation to various private power companies, while its 500-
billion-peso (12.5 billion dollars) debt will be transferred to
the government.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Senator Rodolfo Biazon questioned the motive of the
two solons for making the disclosure, but urged the National
Bureau of Investigation and the Office of the Ombudsman to
investigate the alleged bribe try. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
