<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Girls Status Unimproved in S. Asia: Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The status of girls in South
Asian countries has not seen much improvement in the last decade
despite of efforts towards this end, said experts at a seminar
held here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Although governments and non-governmental organizations in
South Asia have made efforts to promote the rights of girls in the
region, the fundamental gender inequities still exist among most
of the population, said Nigel Fisher, regional director of the
UNICEF (United Nations Children's Fund) at the seminar organized
by the South Asia Partnership International.
</P>
<P>
"Huge gender disparities exist in most countries in the region,
which can be termed as the least gender-sensitive region in the
world," said Fisher.
</P>
<P>
"We have the highest percentage of malnourished girls, the
lowest female literacy rate and the lowest percentage of girls in
schools," he said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, girls in South Asia start to work earlier, become at
increasingly higher risk of violence and exploitation inside and
outside the home, fisher added.
</P>
<P>
Echoing the same view, Minister of State for Women and Social
Welfare of Nepal Kamala Panta said children and women in South
Asia are the marginalized groups living in difficult circumstances.
</P>
<P>
The discrimination between boys and girls begins from birth and
magnifies as they grow, Panta said.
</P>
<P>
Girls have unequal access to schools and many of them are
victims of sexual exploitation, she added.
</P>
<P>
To improve the present unpleasant situations for girls, Fisher
stressed the need to demand accountable leadership at all levels
of governments in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
He said there is a pressing need for legislation and laws to
ensure the rights of women and girls and to provide them with
adequate legal protections.
</P>
<P>
Fisher also appealed for resource allocations for programs
targeted to the education, health and well-being of girls.
</P>
<P>
Attending the two-day seminar are about 30 representatives from
governmental and non-governmental organizations in Canada, Sri
Lanka, Pakistan, India, Bangladesh and Nepal, who discussed the
conditions of girls in South Asia and proposed ways to promote
their status. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
