<HEADLINE> French Supermarket to Bring Partners to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The French supermarket chain
Carrefour is trying to bring its partner producers in France into
the Chinese market, which is considered promising, Le Figaro
newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
During the International Saloon of Food in Beijing, many French
small- and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) are displaying their
products at the invitation of Carrefour.
</P>
<P>
Daniel Bernard, the president of Carrefour, has been engaged in
promoting exports by SMEs, first in countries like Brazil and
Argentina, and now in China, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Jean-Luc Chereau, director of Carrefour in China, said the
consumption structure of high-income population in China is close
to that in France in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
Carrefour estimates that 150 million people in China have
formed a new middle class of consumers whose annual income ranges
from 1,500 to 3,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Carrefour, which is running 23 supermarkets in 14 Chinese
cities, has invested 1 billion francs (147 million U.S. dollars)
in China, and employs 12,000 people.
</P>
<P>
One Carrefour supermarket in Shanghai receives 6 million
customers each year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
