<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Informs U.N. on Withdrawal From Southern Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy
said here on Monday that his country has formally informed United
Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan on its decision to pull its
troops out of southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"I have sent to the secretary general of the U.N. the letter
concerning the decision of the Israeli government to quit Lebanon,
" Levy told the press after a meeting with his French counterpart
Hubert Vedrine.
</P>
<P>
He said the withdrawal will be made in a manner so that it will
be accepted by all sides involved.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine said France still wishes that such a pullout be made
within the framework of a peace agreement between Israel and two
of its Arab neighbors -- Lebanon and Syria.
</P>
<P>
He also warned Israel that some people may take advantage of
the pullout to "create a situation of insecurity."
</P>
<P>
Israel has invited France to participate in a U.N. peacekeeping
operation in southern Lebanon once the pullout is done.
</P>
<P>
France is now discussing with both Israel and the U.N. the
working of such a peacekeeping operation, which will include the
transformation of the role of the U.N. Intermediary Force for
Lebanon which has been installed in Lebanon since 1979.
</P>
<P>
France is also considering receiving some members of the pro-
Israel South Lebanon Army and their families as refugees after the
Israeli pullout. 
</P>
</TEXT>
