<HEADLINE> What Is Going On in Tibet's Prisons (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- "Though it is not as free as the
outside, but beating, scolding and torturing prisoners are totally
forbidden in the prison," said Keni, who is serving a life
imprisonment at the Tibet Autonomous Regional Prison.
</P>
<P>
He added: "I can freely exercise my religious beliefs."
</P>
<P>
Keni is sentenced to life imprisonment for his intentionally
injuring others which leads to the death of a man.
</P>
<P>
Just like other prisoners, he participates in all the
activities arranged by the prison administration, such as learning
to knit cushions.
</P>
<P>
Everyday after the supper, Keni is free to read newspapers,
magazines and books, listen to the radio, watch TV or play chess.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously, prisoners are treated in a humanitarian way,"
commented Kapil Sibal, chairman of the working group for random
detention from the United Nations, when he visited the prison two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
Norbu, an official in charge of the prison, said that there
have been much improvement. A playground and a dining hall have
been built, musical instruments are bought and the quality of food
has increased, Norbu added.
</P>
<P>
According to regulations, each prisoner may have 20 kilograms
of grain, five kilograms of meat and 15 kilograms of vegetables
per month, in addition to a certain amount of tea, ghee and other
non-staple food. Their annual board wages are 1,800 yuan (about
216.86 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Keni said, prisoners manage the canteen themselves on a
democratic basis, and they decide what they want to eat.
</P>
<P>
What is different between Keni and other prisoners is that he
teaches the Tibetan language on Saturdays and Sundays, since he
used to be a Tibetan language teacher at a local primary school.
</P>
<P>
Because of his good behavior, the prison authorities have
applied to local people's court for the reduction of Keni's prison
term.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000417.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> What Is Going On in Tibet's Prisons (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Doctors at the prison said that they conducted regular medical
chick-ups for prisoners and have found that most of them are in
good health.
</P>
<P>
Prisoners who are very sick will be immediately sent to well-
equipped hospitals or be released on bail for medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
Prisoners are also allowed to reunions with their families
during traditional Tibetan festivals, Keni said.
</P>
<P>
Tibet has three prisons which include the Tibet Autonomous
Regional Prison, Lhasa Prison and Bomi Prison. They are
responsible for managing, educating and reforming 2,200 criminals.
</P>
<P>
At present, the number of criminals in local prisons accounts
for 0.9 per thousand of the region's total population.
</P>
<P>
Eighty percent of the prisoners have committed crimes such as
theft, robbery, corruption, murder, and intentionally injuring
others. Five per cent of crimes threaten the national security of
the nation.
</P>
<P>
Among all the prisoners, Tibetan criminals account for 76
percent, those of Han nationality and other ethnic groups, 24
percent. Women criminals make up 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Jamyang Rinchen, warden of the Lhasa Prison, said that the
regional government invests large amount of money in improving
facilities in local prisons every year.
</P>
<P>
He said that in 1999 alone, local government spent more than 7
million yuan (about 843,000 U.S. dollars) in installing new
facilities in cells, dining halls, bath rooms, playgrounds and
recreational centers.
</P>
<P>
Jamyang Rinchen said, prisoners seldom fight with east other
and there is few violations of disciplines in Lhasa Prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000417.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> What Is Going On in Tibet's Prisons (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In addition, prisoners' relatives are invited to act as
supervisors to keep an eye on the activities of police, Losang
Geleg said.
</P>
<P>
He said, local prisons have opened various courses for the
purpose to eliminate illiteracy and implement primary compulsory
education among prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, prisoners are encouraged to learn a certain skill
which enables them to compete for a job when they return to
society.
</P>
<P>
In Lhasa Prison, prisoners can participate in vegetable
planting, automobile repairs, cultivation of flowers, farming,
breeding domestic animals, processing stone materials, repairing
and building houses.
</P>
<P>
Prisoners there work four days a week and six hours a day.
Women prisoners only plant flowers and spin wool, which are not
heavy work.
</P>
<P>
The Tibet Autonomous Regional Prison and the Lhasa Prison both
have built teaching facilities. Losang Geleg said that they employ
a group of professional teachers and select some well-educated
prisoners to act as teachers in the prison-managed "Yuxin Schools".
They teach law, ethics, politics and culture.
</P>
<P>
Prisoners are also encouraged to take part in the examinations
and correspondence education programs launched by cultural and
technical schools. Many of them have obtained diplomas, and some
win prizes at the region's Tibetan calligraphy competition.
</P>
<P>
"I regard the prison term as a school semester," said Yong
Jianxi, a prisoner at the Tibet Autonomous Regional Prison. He
plans to learn and master a special skill and earn his own living
after his release from prison.  
</P>
</TEXT>
