<HEADLINE> High-tech Development Attracts Overseas Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Development of high-tech
industry in China's central and western region is attracting more
and more overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
David Cohen, president and chief executive officer of
TransFiber Industry Holdings, Ltd. of the United States, said that
his company plans to build a wireless telecommunication network in
Henan Province, central China.
</P>
<P>
Cohen is attending a three-day Henan Economic and Trade Fair
which opened Sunday. He signed an agreement of cooperation with
local partners today.
</P>
<P>
Because the network is wireless, there is no need for the
construction of large-scale costly infrastructure facilities, said
Cohen, noting that such project is suitable to China's western
region.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said that with the introduction of new technology people
can watch cable TV, make long distance calls and browse on the
Internet without optical fiber cable.
</P>
<P>
High-tech programs account for more than 50 percent of all Sino-
overseas joint projects at the fair.
</P>
<P>
Li Kam Chung, chairman and chief executive officer of Seven
Star International Holding Inc. of Hong Kong, is also interested
in the high-tech development in the central and western regions of
the country.
</P>
<P>
He has introduced 10 advanced high-tech projects to Henan since
the beginning of the year. Plasma technology for disposing of
garbage won an authentication certificate issued by UN Secretary
General Kofi Annan in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Henan Province has worked out preferential policies which
encourage overseas investors to pour more money into its
electronic technology, bio-science and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Provinces of Shaanxi, Sichuan and Guizhou, and Ningxia Hui
Autonomous Region have also issued similar policies over the past
month.
</P>
<P>
However, experts say that China should avoid the import of high-
tech products which have been phased out by foreign countries or
are harmful to the environment. They also stressed the necessity
to foster high quality high-tech personnel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
