<HEADLINE> Leading Geologists Calls for Research of Dust storms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Two Chinese leading geologists
called today for early launching of dust storm research programs
in the wake of seven dust storms hitting northern China this
spring.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the Science and Technology Daily, Ding Zhongli,
head of Institute of Geology and Geophysics of the Chinese Academy
of Sciences (CAS), and Liu Dongsheng, geologist and CAS scholar,
said that dust storm research is an urgent task for the whole
nation.
</P>
<P>
The Science and Technology Daily quoted the two scientists as
saying that the dust storm could only be curbed after monitoring
regular the patterns of dust storms
</P>
<P>
The occurrence and process of dust storms should also be a
major research program with the help of remote sensing data, they
said.
</P>
<P>
The frequent occurrence of the dust storms in northern China
was also felt in the southern parts of China. The civil aviation
and communications departments were all affected.
</P>
<P>
The dust storms have become a hot topic in the media and among
ordinary Chinese as well.
</P>
<P>
Scientists said all the dust storms come from arid and semi-
arid areas. The largest dust storm emanate from the Sahara Desert
and arid areas in central Asia.
</P>
<P>
They said large amount of dust in the atmosphere from arid
areas in central Asia moved to the Loess Plateau and northern
Pacific areas.
</P>
<P>
They said the Loess Plateau is formed by atmospheric dust blown
from the arid areas by wind and loess accumulation over a long
period of time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
