<HEADLINE> Filipino Terrorists Given Ultimatum to Free Captives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- A local Philippine leader issued
Monday an ultimatum to Abu Sayyaf terrorists, urging them to free
all their hostages until the end of April, otherwise he will
personally lead an all-out assault against them.
</P>
<P>
Wahab Akbar, governor of Basilan province in the southern
Philippines, said in a statement that he has on standby some 500
fully-armed civilians ready to initiate assault at the extremists'
camp if government negotiations fail.
</P>
<P>
"This is an ultimatum, it's either the rebels free all hostages
or face an all-out assault. We will not tolerate terrorism in the
province anymore," Akbar said.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf, which abducted more than 50 hostages in Basilan
province in March, continues to keep 29 civilians hostage and has
reportedly given the Philippine government a one-week deadline to
meet its demands.
</P>
<P>
Abu Sayyaf leader Khaddafy Janjalani sent Philippine President
Joseph Estrada a list of demands last Friday, including the
release of suspected terrorists, stopping the display of Christian
crosses in Sulu, Basilan and Tawi-Tawi, and the removal of all
foreign fishing vessels in the waters of these three provinces.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Armed Forces spokesman Rafael Romero said the
military is taking its steps to address the hostage situation.
</P>
<P>
"The primordial concern is the safety of all the hostages, but
we are not ruling out military action against the Abu Sayyaf,"
Romero said.
</P>
<P>
The rebels have threatened to execute all hostages if the
government attempts a rescue. 
</P>
