<HEADLINE> Cambodia's Garment Exports Fall in 1st Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's top export earner,
the garment industry, is facing a hard year due to the impact of
quota and the factory strikes.
</P>
<P>
According to the figures released by the Commerce Ministry last
weekend, Cambodia exported 123.1 million U.S. dollars worth of
garments during the first three months of the year, down by 5
percent from the previous year's 129.6 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The ministry attributed the decrease to a quota agreement with
the United States that limited the amount manufacturers were
allowed to export to the U.S. and workers' strikes which forced
some factories to close.
</P>
<P>
The figures show that garment exports to the U.S. have fallen
to 93.6 million U.S. dollars in the first quarter from 115.8
million dollars in the same period of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The quota, imposed by the U.S. in January, 1999, put ceilings
on 12 kinds of garment products. Many factories got only a small
share of quotas so they could not survive and those heavily
relying on the U.S. market were also suffering.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia has benefited from the special trade privileges from
the United States since 1996 and low tariffs provided under the
European Union's Generalized System of Preferences. 
</P>
</TEXT>
