<HEADLINE> Johannesburg Stock Exchange Turns Weak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Johannesburg Stock
Exchange (JSE) looks set for further weakness this week with
portfolio managers and dealers bracing for continuing volatility
on fallout from the U.S. markets, a South African financial
analyst said here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The JSE market may bottom out soon but there is little
likelihood of a sharp rebound this week ahead of the Easter
holidays as investors are still edgy over the fallout from the
U.S. technology meltdown, according to assistant general manager
of Amalgamated Bank of South Africa Asset Management Dion
Metcalfe.
</P>
<P>
"I expect more of the same this week. We have never seen these
kinds of volatilities before in the markets and I think there will
be more volatility linked to Wall Street," he said.
</P>
<P>
Wall Street's technology-led falls last Thursday smacked the
JSE to year lows last Friday as investors dumped equities, spooked
by turbulence that has stalked global markets recently.
</P>
<P>
The losses on JSE were overdone and the exchange is now looking
cheap after the market wiped nine percent off share prices over
the past two weeks, Metcalfe said. 
</P>
