<HEADLINE> Mandela Accepts Donation for Mozambican Flood Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Former South African
President Nelson Mandela Monday accepted one million rand (about
154,000 U.S. dollars) from Caltex Oil Company and 500 water
rollers from the Hippo Water Trust on behalf of the Mozambican
flood victims.
</P>
<P>
The donation ceremony was held at Mandela's home residence in
Houghton, Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of Caltex Oil South Africa Dana Flanders said the
company, which has operations in Mozambique, is happy to help the
flood victims rebuild their lives.
</P>
<P>
"The Mozambicans are going through an enormous tragedy. We hope
our donation can help them recover in some way," Flanders said.
</P>
<P>
Regina Nzo, former Secretary General of the African National
Congress and wife of the late former Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo,
said on behalf of the Hippo Water Trust that the rollers could
hold 90 liters of water and could easily be pushed by a small
child.
</P>
<P>
"The rollers will save enormous amounts of time for rural
communities because they are rolled as opposed to being carried
in buckets on the head," Nzo said.
</P>
<P>
The non-profit trust has distributed the rollers on a
subsidized basis to 35 communities throughout Africa. More than
40,000 people have benefited from using them.
</P>
<P>
"The water roller is an exciting African Renaissance
innovation. It is an excellent example of how Africans can develop
solutions to African problems," she said. 
</P>
