<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Countries Reach Compromise on Ivory Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 17 (Xinhua) -- African countries reached a
compromise agreement on ivory trade on Monday as South Africa
agreed to give up its request for an annual export quota of 30
tons of raw ivory.
</P>
<P>
However, at the ongoing 11th Conference of the Parties to the
Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES) in
Kenya's capital Nairobi, South African representatives still
demanded a transfer of its elephant population from CITES Appendix
I to Appendix II.
</P>
<P>
All species in CITES Appendix I are banned on trade while
species in Appendix II are regulated in trade under a strict
monitoring system. South Africa's elephant species being
downlisted to CITES Appendix II will be endorsed by the conference
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kenya and India also withdrew their proposal which
demanded the transfer of the elephant population in Botswana,
Zimbabwe and Namibia currently listed in Appendix II to Appendix
I.
</P>
<P>
At the conference, South Africa had demanded an annual ivory
export quota of 30 tons; Botswana, 12 tons; Namibia, two tons; and
Zimbabwe, 10 tons.
</P>
<P>
The elephant species in Botswana, Namibia and Zimbabwe are
already in Appendix II.
</P>
<P>
It is learned that South Africa can only put forward its
request for export ivory at the next CITES conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
