<HEADLINE> S. Korea U.S. Agree to Launch Computer Network for Patents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 17 (Xinhua) -- South Korea and the United States
Monday agreed to establish a computer network exclusively for
registering patents and trademarks.
</P>
<P>
The Korean Industrial Property Office (KIPO) and the U.S.
Patent and Trademark Office (USPTO) also agreed to cooperate
actively in connecting South Korea to the three-way network of the
United States, Japan and Europe.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, which was reached by KIPO Commissioner Oh Kang-
hyun and USPTO Director-General Todd Dickinson, is aimed at saving
expenses and time needed for registering patents.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to the exchange of personnel and revision
of the bilateral Patent Cooperation Treaty and to exchange
opinions about the standards and protection of the patents on
business models.
</P>
<P>
A KIPO spokesman said working-level officials from both sides
will soon discuss the establishment of the South Korea-U.S. patent
network. 
</P>
