<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Restructuring of China's Securities Sector (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- China's securities sector is
undergoing the second round of restructuring since the mid-1990s,
with companies racing to expand their equity capital, develop
online stocking trading and become China's first publicly-listed
investment banks.
</P>
<P>
The latest wave of equity capital expansion was triggered off
in May 1999 by the Xiangcai Securities Co. in Hunan Province,
which increased its capital from 100 million to one billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
More than a dozen investment banks have raised their capital or
have announced plans to do so. In the first four months of this
year alone, six investment banks announced capital expansion plans.
</P>
<P>
The wave has changed the strength of investment banks in term
of equity capital. The merger of Guotai and Jun'an, both in
Shanghai, established the largest investment bank, Guitai-Jun'an
Securities Co., with a registered capital of 3.7 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
China Communications Securities Co., formerly a relatively
small company, raised its capital to 2.2 billion yuan, ranking
second.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that altogether, investment banks total capital
increased by more than 10 billion yuan, which not only means
stronger investment banks, but also larger capital supply to the
stock market. The process has been accompanied by large scale
merger and restructuring in local securities sector, especially as
local trust and investment companies are involved, often with
encouragement from local governments and securities regulators.
</P>
<P>
For example, the merger of the Chongqing International Trust
and Investment Co. the Chongqing Securities Trading Center and two
other local securities companies produced the Southwest Securities
Co. the largest investment bank in southwest China, with
registered capital of one billion yuan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000417.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
