<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao's Land Area Expanding 0.64 sq.km. per Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The land area of Macao has been
increased from 17.71 sq. km. at the end of 1980s to 24.18 sq. km.
at the end of 1990s, at a speed of 0.64 sq. km. per year,
according to a joint research by scientists from China's mainland
and Macao region.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the expansion is the result of rapid economic
development of Macao from 1980s to 1990s, during which large-scale
seaside land reclamation was carried out.
</P>
<P>
The research, jointly conducted by Beijing-based prestigious
Qinghua University and Macao University, unveiled the close
relationship between economic growth and land expansion, and
indicated that future development of Macao still depends on
further land extension.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, the land area of the peninsula only increased 5.04
sq. km. from 1912 to 1986, or 0.068 sq. km. a year during the 70-
odd years.
</P>
<P>
The research, supported by China's National Natural Science
Foundation, found that the mud and sand brought by the Pearl River
deposit at the western region of the river's mouth to sea,
offering abundant land resources for Macao's seaside land
reclamation.
</P>
<P>
Researchers also drew a digital map at a scale of 1:5000 for
Macao, and studied the change of the Macao's territory over the
past 100 years. The urban air pollution was also under the study
of the scientists.
</P>
<P>
The National Natural Science Foundation Committee recently
provided 425,000 yuan (about 51,000 US dollars) to support a joint
research by universities and institutes in the mainland and Macao
to find a solution to auto emission pollution control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000417.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Reports Good Quality in Snack Foods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The quality of China's snack
foods is relatively good, with a qualification rate of 88.5
percent, showed a recent spot check.
</P>
<P>
The random examination was conducted by the State Bureau of
Quality and Technical Supervision, covering 61 varieties of snacks
including biscuits, puffed food, fried food, soda pop and dairy
drinks, produced by 55 enterprises across China.
</P>
<P>
The examination found that 93.3 percent of the biscuits covered
reaches the national quality standard, and 100 percent of the
puffed food were qualified.
</P>
<P>
The qualification rates for the fried food, soda pop and dairy
drinks were 77.8 percent, 80 percent and 83.3 percent,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
About 97 percent of the examined large and medium-sized
enterprises were up to standard, while the qualification rate for
small enterprises was 78.6 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
