<HEADLINE> 5 Israelis Convicted in Maccabiah Bridge Disaster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Five Israelis were found guilty
in the case of the bridge collapse disaster in Israel during the
Maccabiah Games in 1997, an Israeli court announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
The five, who played key organizational roles in the games,
should be responsible for their negligence causing death and
injuries, said Tel Aviv Magistrate's Court. The defendants are
facing a maximum prison term of four years.
</P>
<P>
The tragedy took place on the occasion of the opening ceremony
of the 15th Maccabiah Games, the Jewish Olympics, on July 14, 1997,
in which four Australian Jewish athletes were killed and nearly
seventy injured.
</P>
<P>
When the Australians were crossing a temporary footbridge over
the Yarkon River into the Ramat Gan stadium near Tel Aviv, the
bridge collapsed and about 100 people were plunged into the
polluted river.
</P>
<P>
The engineer who designed the bridge, two sub-contractors, the
head of the Games' organizing committee, and the manager of the
Irgunit company which supplied materials for the bridge were
charged with causing death by negligence and building without
proper permits.
</P>
<P>
The trial officially began on January 20, 1998 and ended last
October. The court rendered its verdict on Monday after almost six
months' deliberation.
</P>
<P>
The victims of the bridge disaster also filed separate civil
complaints against 19 Israeli entities, including the state,
police, Maccabi Israel and the Ramat Gan Municipality, to seek
damages of more than one million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
An attorney representing the victims said that he believed a
guilty verdict in the criminal case would directly help speed up
the compensation claims in the civil suit, which is currently under
way in Tel Aviv District Court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
