<HEADLINE> Only 2 percent of Poor Dhaka Citizens Support Hartal: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Only two percent of the poor city
dwellers support hartal (general strike) in principle as a means
of protest, according to a survey released here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The survey on "Hartal and the Poor of Dhaka City" was conducted
by a social survey unit of Democracy Watch from January 27 to 31
this year to ascertain the income loss of the poor city dwellers
during hartals and to look into their overall perceptions on
hartal.
</P>
<P>
The survey said that moral support for hartal or support to any
political leader is very insignificant case for work stoppage,
suggesting a very low level of political affiliation of the poor
city dwellers.
</P>
<P>
On the alternative means of protest and political activity, 67
percent of the poor desire the parliament to be more effective as
the forum of political discussion while 21 percent of them support
meetings and processions as a vehicle of political protest by the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, most city dwellers do not support
hartal because they suffer most in terms of economic loss as well
as income loss, and they witness a lot of damage to their
properties during such political programs.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,000 poor dwellers of Dhaka city were interviewed
through a questionnaire as hartal has become pervasive in
Bangladesh, disrupting normal life with a telling effect on the
poor like rickshaw-pullers, day laborers, small shopkeepers and
slum dwellers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
