<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Receives 1.37 Bln U.S. Dollars of FDI in 9 months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Direct Investment (FDI) to
Bangladesh was registered at 1.47 billion U.S. dollars by the
Board of Investment (BOI) during the first nine months of the
current fiscal year (1999-2000), Executive Chairman of BOI
Mokammel Haque told a workshop Monday.
</P>
<P>
The flow of FDI is increasing in the country as the present
government has offered a package of incentives and taken a number
of initiatives to create an investment friendly atmosphere, Haque
said.
</P>
<P>
The BOI chief said government is giving priority to setting up
agro-based industries in the country. The BOI has taken various
measures to help the investors in providing sewerage, electricity
and gas within the shortest time, he added.
</P>
<P>
Haque said different companies from countries like the United
States, Britain and Japan had registered their names for investing
in oil, gas and power sectors while some companies of Malaysia,
United Arab Emirates and Singapore are in ceramic and tourism
industries.
</P>
<P>
The workshop on "Investment Guides and Capacity-Building for
Least-Developed Countries" was jointly organized by the United
Nations Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD), the
International Chamber of Commerce (ICC)- Bangladesh, the World
Business Organization and the BOI.
</P>
<P>
President of ICC-Bangladesh Mahabubur Rahman said in the
opening remarks that UNCTAD and ICC have launched a joint
initiative on investment guides and capacity-building for the
least-developed countries (LDCs) with a view to addressing some of
the difficulties faced by LDCs in attracting FDI.
</P>
<P>
The project has two components: the preparation of investment
guides which provide objective and up-to-date information on
investment conditions in individual LDCs and investment-related
capacity-building in LDCs, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
