<HEADLINE> Share Prices Take Serious Plunge on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Share prices took a battering
on Singapore Stock Market Monday in line with other Asian markets
in reaction to Friday's steep tumble on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index plunged to 1,999.39 points at
close, dropping 190.37 points or 8.69 percent, the largest single
day point fall since October 1987.
</P>
<P>
The total volume surged up to 410.16 million shares worth 932.
29 million Singapore dollars (about 545.20 million U.S. dollars).
Declining issues overwhelmed advancers by 386 to 9 with 136
counters unchanged.
</P>
<P>
OngAisa topped the volume list as it registered a turnover of
27.83 million units. MediaRing was the second most heavily-traded
stock with 17.04 million shares done. GES was the next with 14.37
million shares changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Poh Lian led gainers with a marginal 4.5 cents increase to end
at 0.60 Singapore dollars. Guthrie and Noble each gained 2.5 cents
to finish at 0.375 and 0.63 Singapore dollars respectively.
Vicplas went up 1.5 cents to end at 0.306 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Creative 50 continued to lead the descent of the day with a 7.5-
dollar plunge to close at 36.10 Singapore dollars. Venture shed
310 cents to finish at 18.00 Singapore dollars. PacCent closed
down 300 cents to end at 14.10 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers noted that the sell-down was across the board with
interest-rate sensitive counters like banking and property stocks,
and technology stocks all being hit.
</P>
<P>
Singapore's four largest banks-- DBS Group, OCBC, Overseas
Union Bank and United Overseas Bank--accounted for a quarter of
the STI's erosion.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the worst is yet to come for local shares
amid concerns over an imminent correction on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
Some analyst said the key index which has fallen below the 2,
000 psychological point, may scroll back to 1,700-1,800 point
level while some recommended bargaining hunting for the deep-
pocketed banking and electronic stocks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
