<HEADLINE> Philippine Extremist Group Threatens to Kill Americans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Philippine extremist group Abu
Sayyaf threatened Monday to kill Americans in Mindanao in the
southern Philippines unless its demand for the release of three
Muslims jailed in the United States is met.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf, which abducted more than 50 hostages in March,
said in a statement that the U.S. government must release the
three Muslims jailed in America, including Ramzi Yousef, the
mastermind in the 1993 bombing of the World Trade Center in New
York.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. embassy to the Philippines made no comment to the
demand of the extremist group, but reminded the 100,000 Americans
living in the Philippines to refrain from traveling to Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Philippine President Joseph Estrada said he is
leaving to the crisis management committee (CMC) the matter of
dealing with the Abu Sayyaf for the safe release of the hostages.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf continues to keep 29 civilians hostage and has
reportedly given the Philippine government a one-week deadline to
meet its demands.
</P>
<P>
National Security Adviser Alexander Aguirre said the CMC
continues to exert efforts to convince the extremists to make
their demand reasonable.
</P>
<P>
Abu Sayyaf leader Khaddafy Janjalani sent President Estrada a
list of the group's demand last Friday, including the release of
suspected terrorists, stopping the display of Christian crosses in
Sulu, Basilan and Tawi-Tawi, and the removal of all foreign
fishing vessels in the waters of these three provinces.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Senator Rodolfo Biazon, for his part, urged the
country's Muslim leaders to use their power of persuasion in
convincing the Abu Sayyaf group to drop its irresponsible demand
and release the hostages.
</P>
<P>
By demanding the release of international terrorists Ramzi
Yousef, Abu Haider and Sheik Abdurahman Omar, Biazon said the Abu
Sayyaf is just trying to internationalize the hostage situation.
</P>
</TEXT>
