<HEADLINE> S. Korean Stocks Plunge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 17 (Xinhua) -- South Korean stock markets suffered
record losses on "Black Monday" in the wake of the crash on Wall
Street at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The Korea Composite Stock Price Index (KOSPI) plummeted more
than 90 points just four minutes after the opening bell Monday
morning, prompting stock authorities to use a circuit breaker for
the first time to halt trading for 20 minutes for a cool-off.
</P>
<P>
The KOSPI lost more than 100 points for the first time before
closing the day at 707.72, down 93.17 points, or 11.63 percent.
</P>
<P>
The KOSPI saw trade volume total 287.7 million shares worth 2.
97 trillion won (2.66 billion U.S. dollars). The floor was
virtually empty in the afternoon with the key index tumbling by 11
percent.
</P>
<P>
Losers outnumbered gainers 837 against 45 with 266 falling by
daily lows.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the KOSDAQ market nosedived too, with seven out of
10 stocks falling by their daily lows.
</P>
<P>
The key index tumbled a record 11.4 percent, or 22.33 points,
to 173.54.
</P>
<P>
The KOSPI and KOSDAQ saw some 40 trillion won worth of market
capitalization vanished due to the crash in stock prices.
</P>
<P>
The KOSPI registered market capitalization of 252.8 trillion
won, down 32.1 trillion won from Friday while that of KOSDAQ
market was slashed by 7.5 trillion won to 107.18 trillion won.
</P>
<P>
The reduced amount was equivalent to 43 percent of the South
Korean national budget for this year.
</P>
<P>
South Korean President Kim Dae-jung has instructed his cabinet
to map out measures to stabilize the faltering stock markets.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said some strong measures to protect the markets are
needed urgently as eventual collapse will be detrimental to the
overall growth of the South Korean economy, especially the
economic restructuring.
</P>
<P>
(One U.S. dollar is about 1,110 won.) 
</P>
</TEXT>
