<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Steel Prices Pick Up in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Prices for some steel products
have been on the rise in northern and eastern China as the
industry's efforts to curb steel production begins to take effect.
</P>
<P>
The prices of steel for construction surged an average of 50-
100 yuan per ton, compared with April 1 this year, after nine
steel giants in the northern provinces announced a rise in the
price of this particular product.
</P>
<P>
The price for steel sheet went up 300-350 yuan per ton compared
with the level in January this year. These price hikes are the
biggest in years, experts note.
</P>
<P>
"The positive change has reversed the long doldrums of the
steel market, providing opportunities for steel enterprises to
step up restructuring and gain better economic returns," they
point out.
</P>
<P>
Experts attribute the price rise to a set of circumstances.
Internationally, the price rise on the global market boosted steel
exports, easing the imbalance of domestic supply and demand.
Domestically, China's efforts to curb production have taken effect
and the beginning of infrastructure projects nationwide,
especially in the western region, strongly bolstered domestic
demand for building materials.
</P>
<P>
They also point out that the price increase of some basic
materials, such as coal and coke, also triggered the surge in
steel prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
