<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stock Suffers Biggest Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Australian stock market
suffered its biggest one-day fall in more than two years Monday,
with more than 36 billion Australian dollars wiped off the value
of the all ordinaries index.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index closed 176.0 points down, or
5.68 percent, at 2920.0.
</P>
<P>
News Corp and technology stocks led the sell-off, which was
just under the dive of October 28, 1997, when the market closed
177.8 points lower.
</P>
<P>
The newly introduced S&AMP;P/ASX 200 was 168.0 points or 5.4
percent lower at 2943.9 points.
</P>
<P>
The falls follow a plunge on Wall Street on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Market heavyweight News Corp bore the brunt of Monday's crash
with its biggest one-day fall in nine years, accounting for almost
one-third of the total decline in the all ordinaries. Its ordinary
shares were down 2.85 Australian dollars to close at 17.75, while
its preferred scrip plunged 2.378 Australian dollars to close at
15.136.
</P>
<P>
Kerry Packer's Publishing &AMP; Broadcasting fell 1.334 Australian
dollars to 11.666, while Fairfax was 48.8 cents down at 4.95
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Among telco stocks, market leader Telstra sank a relatively
modest 37 cents at 7.12 Australian dollars. C&AMP;W Optus lost 61.6
cents at 5.36 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 952.32 million shares at a value of 1.879
billion (113.82 million U.S. dollars). Falls outpaced rises 465 to
382, with 368 stocks steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
