<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Businessmen Asked to Tap BIMP-EAGA Potentials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Businessmen have
been urged to explore the tremendous potentials in the Brunei-
Indonesia- Malaysia-Philippines East ASEAN Growth Area (BIMP-EAGA).
</P>
<P>
BIMP-EAGA Malaysian Business Council (BEMBC) Advisor Abdul
Rahman Maidin said Monday that complimentary resources of member
countries could be harnessed through the regional economic
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia with its high skilled manufacturing technology,
services and finance sectors could, for example, compliment
Indonesia's surplus of labor, land and natural resources and labor
intensive light manufacturing, he said at a seminar in conjunction
with the launching of the BEMBC in Kuching, Sarawak, East Malaysia,
according to Bernama news agency.
</P>
<P>
He called upon businessmen to look into the possibility of
developing border towns or friendship cities as part of the
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He said that Trans-Borneo land-based fiber optic system, Trans-
Borneo-Mindanao railway system and establishment of timber
terminals are some of the potentials in the region's
infrastructure and timber sectors.
</P>
<P>
The agro-tourism, human resources, information technology and
herbal industries also hold vast opportunities for investment, he
said.
</P>
<P>
At present there are 11 working groups in the BIMP-EAGA
including air and sea linkages, joint tourism development and
fisheries cooperation, he said.
</P>
<P>
The BIMP-EAGA participating regions -- Brunei, the Indonesian
provinces of Kalimantan, Sulawesi, Maluku Islands and Irian Jaya
as well as Malaysia's Sarawak, Sabah and Labuan and Philippines'
Mindanao and Pahlawan -- currently have a combined population of
30 million including a labor force of 11.3 million.
</P>
<P>
The BIMP-EAGA's population was expected to swell to 44 million
by 2010 when 18 million labor force would be anticipated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000417.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 23 Rebels Killed in Northern Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan Defense Ministry
Monday said government troops killed 23 Tamil rebels on Sunday in
a fresh outbreak of fighting in the northern Jaffna Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Government troops engaged a group of rebels in general area
Kattaratan and Paddikkudiyiruppu on Sunday morning, killing eight
rebels, the ministry spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday afternoon in general area Kudarapu, government troops
confronted a group of Tamil rebels, killing at least five "Tigers".
Subsequently rebels retaliated with mortars injuring one soldier,
the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He added that in another incident during the day in general
area Veddukadu and Kovilkadu, troops sniped and killed at least 10
rebels.
</P>
<P>
The Tamil rebels are engaged in an ongoing offensive aimed at
taking control of Jaffna Peninsula, their stronghold which the
government troops recaptured in May 1996.
</P>
<P>
The rebels, who have been fighting a war against the government
since 1983 for a separate Tamil state in the country, now main
target appears to be Elephant pass, the main road link between the
peninsula and the mainland.
</P>
<P>
The rebels launched their operation, called Oyantha Alaikal at
Elephant Pass last December.
</P>
<P>
Fighting has intensified since 26 March this year, and over 120
soldiers have been reportedly killed since that time. The Defense
Ministry early said the Tamil rebels had lost more than 300
fighters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
