<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Environmental Activist Acquitted of Spying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Supreme Court on
Monday declared former Navy Captain Alexander Nikitin not guilty
of spying and divulging state secrets.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court's criminal cases collegium upheld Nikitin's
acquittal by the St. Petersburg city court on December 29, 1999,
and rejected an appeal against the sentence filed by the city's
Prosecutor's Office, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Security Service, the main successor to the Soviet
KGB, had brought charges of high treason and spying against
Nikitin, who wrote a report on radiation safety in Russia's
Northern Fleet for the Norwegian ecological organization Bellona
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court ruled that Nikitin's activities had not been
punishable when he was engaged in them, nor was a list available
of secret data. The court could not therefore continue looking
into the case.
</P>
<P>
Because the prosecutor involved in the case believed that the
investigation had been thorough, the court ruled that there was no
reason why it should continue.
</P>
<P>
The acquittal of Nikitin by the St. Petersburg city court takes
effect as of Monday, but the Prosecutor General's Office may
appeal it again to the Supreme Court presidium, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
Nikitin had been held in a St. Petersburg remand center for 10
months in 1996 and was not allowed to leave town.
</P>
<P>
He welcomed the ruling by the Supreme Court, describing it as
an indication that the law is in force in Russia. Nikitin also
said he would continue environment protection activities.
</P>
<P>
He said he also plans to visit his wife and daughter, who
reside in Canada, Interfax said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
