<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Unemployment Rate Edges Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 17 (Xinhua) -- A senior government economist
Monday announced that Hong Kong's unemployment rate edged down in
the latest period, along with a further pick-up in overall
economic activity.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Special Administrative Region Government
Economist K Y Tang said the underemployment rate, however, showed
some increase, conceivably due to a greater number of the earlier
unemployed persons being engaged as temporary or part-time workers.
</P>
<P>
The provisional seasonally adjusted unemployment rate for the
first three months this year was 5.6 percent, and the provisional
underemployment rate was 2.8 percent, according to the latest
labor force statistics released Monday by the Census and
Statistics Department.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary for Education and Manpower Joseph W P Wong said
that in line with the recovery in the economy, more jobs were
available in the labor market.
</P>
<P>
"In March the number of vacancies registered with the Labor
Department set a record high level of 18,400 representing a 35
percent increase over the same month last year," Wong said. "
Increases were generally recorded across the board in most
industry and occupational groups", he added.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Local Employment Services of the Labor
Department also showed that more job-seekers had succeeded in
finding jobs. In March, the department found jobs for over 5,300
job seekers.
</P>
<P>
"This is the highest number of monthly job placements since the
start of its employment services, and represents a 50 percent
increase over March 1999," Wong said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
