<DOCNO> XIE20000417.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Archaeology News: Weekly Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The following is a round-up of
Xinhua's archaeology news for the past week:
</P>
<P>
-- 1,200-Year-Old Stone Cave Found in Xinjiang
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists in western Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region
recently stumbled upon a stone cave of the Tang Dynasty (618-907)
decorated with delicate frescos painted on the walls and roof.
</P>
<P>
The frescos in the cave, 70 kilometers north of Kuche County,
depict Buddhas and Buddhist rituals, the archaeologists said.
</P>
<P>
They believe the 20-square-meter cave is a remnant of ancient
Buddhist culture in Qiuzi, which prevailed in the Tang Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
-- China Stresses Fire Prevention at Heritage Sites
</P>
<P>
China's State Administration of Cultural Heritage (SACH) has
issued a circular requesting localities to tighten fire safety
measures at heritage sites throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
The state's highest relics protection authorities urged local
administrations to strictly control combustible or explosive
substances near these sites.
</P>
<P>
Relics experts suggest greater precautions against fires during
the dry spring period.
</P>
<P>
-- Ancient Senior Official's Tomb Rich in Relics
</P>
<P>
After four and a half months of excavation in rural areas of
northwestern Shaanxi Province, a great number of cultural relics
were discovered in a Tang Dynasty (618-907) tomb.
</P>
<P>
The 60-meter-long tomb of Gao Lishi, a powerful eunuch during
the Tang, contained 220 earthenware articles and frescos.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000417.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Archaeology News: Weekly Briefs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- 128 Million Tourists Visit Dingling Tomb Museum
</P>
<P>
The Dingling Tomb Museum in the northern suburbs of Beijing has
attracted 128 million tourists from around the world since it
opened 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Museum authorities recently held a special ceremony to
celebrate this accomplishment, and presented a replica of a dragon
robe and the formal clothes of a Chinese emperor to a visitor from
the United States. The lucky American and his relatives were also
given lifetime passes to the museum.
</P>
<P>
-- Shanghai Museum To Show Relics of Nomadic Tribes
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Museum plans to organize a large exhibition from
July 1 to November 30 featuring cultural relics of ancient nomadic
tribes in north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The 300 heritage articles date from the Neolithic Period to the
Yuan Dynasty (1271-1368).
</P>
<P>
-- Yellow Emperor's Tomb Fund Attracts 51.2 Million Yuan
</P>
<P>
Donations from home and abroad for the renovation of the
Mausoleum of Huangdi (the Yellow Emperor), the legendary founder
of the Chinese nation, have reached 51.2 million yuan (about 6.2
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
According to the Fund for the Mausoleum of Huangdi, donations
have been very active since the fund was established in 1992, the
same year renovation of the mausoleum began.
</P>
<P>
Shaanxi Province in northwest China began the renovation, as
more and more overseas Chinese began returning to China to pay
their respects to Huangdi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
