<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukrainians Overwhelmingly Approve Constitutional Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainians overwhelmingly approved
changes to their constitution which could increase the power of
President Leonid Kuchma over parliament, the electoral commission
announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
A Sunday referendum proposed four amendments to Ukraine's
constitution including allowing the president to dissolve
parliament and reducing the number of parliamentary deputies from
450 to 300.
</P>
<P>
Other provisions would divide the legislature into an upper and
lower house and strip deputies of immunity in certain cases.
</P>
<P>
With 94 percent of votes counted, each of the four proposals
received between 81 percent and 90 percent support, Ukraine's
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Kuchma expressed that "the mission of the president,
as the guarantor of the constitution, is to ensure the will of the
people, if the parliament is not able to do so."
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Kuchma, elected in 1994 and reelected
last November, has reportedly had strained relations with
parliament which he accuses of blocking his reform projects.
</P>
</TEXT>
