<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Run 3,000 Tourism Trains This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Railways will
operate 3,000 to 4,000 tourism trains this year in response to the
government's strategy for boosting tourism to develop the national
economy.
</P>
<P>
This decision was made a national working conference on China's
special trains for tourism held recently in Kunming, capital of
southwest China's Yunnan Province.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also decided to accelerate the speed and improve
the service of the country's special tourism trains.
</P>
<P>
China began to put into service these special trains in 1997,
and they have proved very popular among domestic and overseas
passengers.
</P>
<P>
In 1999 alone, the Ministry of Railways opened 11 train routes
to this tourist destination from the country's eight major
terminals, running a total of 932 tourism trains and transporting
5.32 million passengers.
</P>
<P>
Despite the obvious social and economic benefits from the
special trains, ministry officials attending the conference said
China's development of such trains is still in its primary stage,
and they cited their slow speeds and multiple stops.
</P>
<P>
The just-ended conference was an attempt to solve these
problems and improve the service on special tourism trains, they
added.
</P>
<P>
The conference also decided to authorize all local railway
bureaus to give 10 to 25 percent discounts for tourism train
tickets, they noted.
</P>
<P>
Sources with the conference disclosed that the Railways
Ministry also plans to open 26 special tourism train routes across
the country, covering major national scenic spots such as Emei
Mountain in southwest China's Sichuan Province, the Turpan Basin
in western China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, Zhangjiajie
in central China's Hunan Province, and Mount Huangshan in east
China's Anhui Province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000417.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Urges Silk Enterprises to Upgrade Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- China is urging state-owned silk
enterprises to upgrade their reeling machines and undertake
innovation in techniques, designs and colors.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-nine programs will be carried out in the enterprises for
technical innovations with 1.54 billion yuan in subsidized loans,
according to a report of Beijing Review.
</P>
<P>
China will reduce silk industry's production by one-third this
year in an effort to improve the sector's economic returns.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-four state-owned silk enterprises will go bankrupt, and
banks will be saddled with writing off 1.36 billion yuan in bad
debts.
</P>
<P>
State-owned silk reeling factories will get help to ease their
social burdens and to lower their debt-to-equity ratios, according
to the State Textile Industry Administration.
</P>
<P>
Seventeen silk enterprises will be allowed to launch debt-to-
equity swaps in 2000, and this involves 2.02 billion yuan in
capital.
</P>
<P>
The silk sector made 320 million yuan of profits during the
first 11 months of 1999 after years of government efforts to
reform the industry.
</P>
<P>
But about 65 percent of the state-owned silk enterprises are
losing money.
</P>
<P>
China's silk exports totaled 2.8 billion U.S. dollars last year,
as against 3.5 billion dollars in 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000417.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sugar Prices Continue to Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- China's sugar prices continued to
rise in April, bringing an optimistic view of profitability by
year's end among insiders.
</P>
<P>
Latest figures show that the sugar prices in Nanning, capital
of south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, a major sugar
distribution center, reached 3,150 yuan (about 380 U.S. dollars)
per ton.
</P>
<P>
Along with restructuring the sugar industry, reduced production
of sugar cane incurred by a frost last year has played an
important role in the price hike.
</P>
<P>
Analysts from the China Sugar Association warned of a drop in
sugar prices next year, and urged sugar producers not to be too
optimistic about the market outlook.
</P>
<P>
Some areas that are unsuitable for sugar production should be
forced to leave the market, while the remaining ones ought to be
required to speed up technical upgrading and enhance efficiency,
they suggested.
</P>
<P>
The retail price of sugar will not be affected much due to the
current large stockpiles and the gap between wholesale prices and
retail prices, according to market sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
