<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Remote Sensing Tech Used to Monitor Urban Land Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- China is employing satellite
remote sensing technology to monitor land use in its urban areas
in order to strengthen the administration of land resource.
</P>
<P>
A total of 66 large cities with populations over 500,000
including Beijing and Shanghai are now being monitored by the
Ministry of Land and Resources.
</P>
<P>
Satellite images show that eight cities made false land use
reports last year, and 19 unapproved land use projects, illegally
occupying 2,800 mu (about 186.7 hectares) of land, were detected
and shut down in time, thanks to the remote sensing technology.
</P>
<P>
The technology will effectively check the occupying of
cultivated land, said Li Yuan, vice minister of land and resources.
</P>
<P>
According to latest statistics from the ministry, China's total
cultivated land area decreased 6.549 million mu (about 436,600
hectares) in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The revised Land Use Law which became effective in 1999 is
considered the strictest in the world. This law requires that all
provinces, autonomous regions, and municipalities must see to it
that the amount of arable land under their jurisdiction will not
decrease, while land quality must be improved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000417.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rainfall Forecast for Areas Along Lower, Middle Reaches of Yangtze River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Some areas along the lower and
middle reaches of the Yangtze River are expected to see rain
during Monday to Wednesday this week and some areas in northern
China are likely to experience dusty and overcast weather, China's
Central Meteorological Observatory said today.
</P>
<P>
The observatory said snowfall (rainfall) ranging from two to
six mm is forecast for the eastern part of the Qinghai-Tibet
Plateau.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, precipitation of three to 20 mm is
expected for the eastern part of southwest China, the Hanshui
River Basin, most part of the area between the Yellow and Huaihe
rivers, the area between the Yangtze and Huaihe rivers, and most
of the area between the Yangtze River and the Nanling Mountians,
and the western part of south China.
</P>
<P>
But for Guizhou Province, eastern part of Hubei Province, and
most part of both the Yangtze-Huaihe area and part of the western
and northern Yangtze-Nanling Mountains area, the rainfall is
forecast to be 30 to 60 mm.
</P>
<P>
Part of northwest and north China is expected to have dusty,
overcast and rainy weather conditions during Monday to Wednesday
this week as a cold air current from western Siberia is forecast
to sweep across most part of China to the north of the Huaihe
River. 
</P>
</TEXT>
