<HEADLINE> Pakistan to Set up Software Technology Parks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan plans to set up
software technology parks in its three main cities in a bid to
speed up the development of information technology in the country.
</P>
<P>
Under a new Information Technology (IT) policy being framed by
the government, initially three Information Technology Parks will
be established in the capital of Islamabad and the two biggest
cities, Karachi and Lahore, state-run Associated Press of Pakistan
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Director General of Pakistan Computer Bureau Ejaz Hussain
Khawaja was quoted as saying that all facilities relating to
computer and information technology will be provided in the parks.
</P>
<P>
Even space will be allocated on payment in the said parks for
use by private parties which will promote IT industry in Pakistan,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Ejaz said Pakistan has great potential to export software to
earn foreign exchange for the country, but initially a sectoral
allocation of an estimated five billion rupees (96 million U.S.
dollars) needs to be invested.
</P>
<P>
IT industry is among the four key sectors the current Pakistani
government has put special emphasis on in its economic reform plan.
The government hopes to stimulate the economic growth by imitating
its neighbor India, which has become the second largest software
exporter in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
