<HEADLINE> Indonesia Has More Chinese Mandarin Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The number of newspapers which
are printed in Chinese Mandarin language has increased in
Indonesia since reform process started in 1998.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the Indonesian Shang Bao daily was formally printed,
bringing the number of Mandarin newspapers in the country to nine.
</P>
<P>
The daily focuses its report on economics and business issues.
</P>
<P>
General Chairman of the Indonesia Shang Bao, Sukamdani Sahid
Gitosardjono said in a press conference that the daily also
targets its readers abroad.
</P>
<P>
"We also targeted the readers of the Indonesia Shang Bao abroad.
Particularly Chinese ethnic business people," he said.
</P>
<P>
After reform process took place following the step down of
former president Soeharto in May 1998, the number of Chinese
Mandarin newspapers have kept increasing. At present, the people
in three cities, such as Jakarta, capital of Indonesia, Medan and
Surabaya could all read Mandarin newspapers.
</P>
<P>
In the past 32 years when Soeharto was in power, Chinese
Mandarin language was barred to be learned by Indonesian and
Chinese ethnic people as well.
</P>
<P>
"But now the situation is different. The Chinese Mandarin
language is free to be learned by every body," Gitosardjono added.
</P>
</TEXT>
