<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zanzibar Opposition Against Polling Date </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Zanzibar's main opposition
party, the Civic United Front (CUF), has opposed the scheduled
date for this year' s general elections on the ground that
President Salmin Amour will have overstayed his term in office by
then, newspapers here reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Zanzibar Electoral Commission has set October 29 as the
polling day in the island state in tandem with parliamentary and
presidential elections on mainland Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
However, Leader of the Opposition in the House of
Representatives in the Isles Abubakar Khamis Bakary told the press
on Sunday that President Salmin was sworn in on October 26, 1995,
therefore his term should cease on or before the same date of this
year.
</P>
<P>
Holding elections on October 29 is a violation of the
constitution, Bakary stressed.
</P>
<P>
According to the Zanzibar Constitution, general elections must
be held within 30 days before the expire of tenure of the
president.
</P>
<P>
The CUF may seek the intervention of the court of law if the
Zanzibar Government does not change the election date, Bakary
said.
</P>
<P>
Though it joined with Tanganyika to form the United Republic of
Tanzania in 1964, Zanzibar is a semiautonomous state with its own
government an parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
