<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania's COMESA Pull-out to be Discussed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- A comprehensive report on
Tanzania's decision to quit the Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA) is to be tabled at the forthcoming heads
of state summit in Mauritius next month.
</P>
<P>
The report, which was compiled by the council of ministers
after a recent mission to Tanzania, would be among the major items
to be discussed at the summit, said COMESA secretary general
Erastus Mwencha in an interview at the weekend in Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted by Monday's Times of Zambia newspaper as saying
that the secretariat is concerned at the decision by Tanzania to
leave the regional bloc.
</P>
<P>
A lot of behind-the-scene diplomatic negotiations are currently
going on to ensure that the country remains a member of COMESA
before the implementation of the Free Trade Area (FTA) later this
year, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said Tanzania is an important trading partner in the region
because it provides port services to some land locked countries
including Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Apart from that, Tanzania is also a major transpoint for the
COMESA yellow card scheme, Mwencha said.
</P>
<P>
"Tanzania has a trade surplus with all COMESA trading partners
except Kenya," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Tanzania gave notice in September last
year on its decision to quit COMESA on account of a membership
duplication between the regional bloc and the Southern African
Development Community (SADC).
</P>
<P>
Tanzania feared that the FTA would reduce its productive
capacity to compete favorably at regional level, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
