<HEADLINE> Law on Land Unchanged in Zambia: Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Law on land ownership in Zambia
will remain the same and white farmers including new settlers
should not fear that the Zambian government will repossess their
land, said Agriculture Minister Suresh Desai here at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
When asked by some farmers whether the grabbing of land in
Zimbabwe would spill over into Zambia, the minister said the
Zambian government would not grab land from its rightful owners as
it would continue to respect land ownership laws.
</P>
<P>
The government has respected land ownership through title deeds
and would continue to allow private investors to develop the
agriculture sector, he was quoted by Monday's Times of Zambia
newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
The government has empowered both commercial and local farmers
with land for agricultural development, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Desai, the land disputes in neighboring Zimbabwe
are tied to the political history in the country, while Zambia has
no problems on commercial land ownership.
</P>
<P>
"Zambia has plenty of land that needs to be developed to
enhance economic development," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister, however, warned that the government would
repossess undeveloped land from any category of ownership.
</P>
