<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Nosedive in Tokyo on Wall Street Plunge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices nosedived across the
board in Tokyo Monday following last Friday's plunge on Wall
Street, with the key Nikkei index posting its fifth-largest one-
day point loss.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 1,426.04 points, or 6.98
percent, from last Friday's close to end at 19,008.64.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, fell 101.24 points, or 6.12 percent, to 1,
552.46, also posting its fifth-largest one-day point fall.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section increased to 875.11 million
shares from last Friday's 683.45 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
Top monetary officials from the Group of Seven (G-7) economies
showed reticence about last Friday's Wall Street plunge in their
statement released after they met Saturday in Washington, making
investors uncomfortable, traders said.
</P>
<P>
After opening at the day's high of 20,341.50, the Nikkei lost
more than 1,800 points at one stage in the morning to fall as low
as 18,603.87.
</P>
<P>
The key market gauge, however, rebounded moderately in the
afternoon, helped partly by a remark by Shizuka Kamei, chairman of
the ruling Liberal Democratic Party's (LDP) Policy Research
Council, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Kamei was quoted as saying the LDP will discuss measures to
cope with the stock market plunge, including an injection of more
than 1 trillion yen (9.6 billion U.S. dollars) in public funds
into the market.
</P>
<P>
In Tokyo on Monday, share prices were lower in all business
sectors except the electric power and gas industry.
</P>
<P>
Exporters were dampened by the savage decline on Wall Street
and the yen's strength, while high-priced telecommunication issues
also fell sharply.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers far
outnumbered gainers 1,236 to 113, with 35 issues closing unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
