<HEADLINE> Russian Shares Tumble 7-10 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Russian shares plunged by 7-10
percent on opening Monday in reaction to the tech stock slides on
world markets, but officials said the crash on Wall Street "will
not have serious consequences for the Russian market."
</P>
<P>
Volumes totaled 2.34 million U.S. dollars on the Russian
Trading System (RTS) by 11:15 a.m. (0700 GMT), the Interfax news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The RTS-Interfax composite ruble index tumbled 6.26 percent to
205.25. The index in dollars was down 6.16 percent to 42.92,
Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
But the drop in Russian share prices was not accompanied by a
sell-off, a development seen by traders as more of a correction
following the global downturn.
</P>
<P>
First Deputy Prime Minister Mikhail Kasyanov, once Russia's
Finance Minister, told reporters there would be a modest drop in
Russian share prices, but that the slump will be "not so great and
sharp" as seen after Russia's financial crisis in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
U.S. shares plunged Friday on fears that an unexpected surge in
inflation could push the Federal Reserve to raise interest rates.
The technology-laden Nasdaq index plummeted a record 9.67 percent
to 3,321.29 points and the Dow Jones index fell a record 617.78
points (5.66 percent) to 10,305.77.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the Russian ruble also went down
Monday, from 28.4950 to 28.6035 to the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
In total, 1,982 transactions worth 167.271 million dollars were
concluded on the Moscow Interbank Currency Exchange (MICEX),
Interfax reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
