<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Huge Potential in China's Aviation Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive Officer of China
Southern Airlines Yan Zhiqing today forecast a rosy future for the
nation's aviation industry, with an anticipated annual growth of
more than 10 percent in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
Unbalanced supply and demand in China's aviation market at
present does not mean the market is saturated, Yan said at the
ongoing China Business Summit, stressing that the market is far
from fully tapped.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, people in the United States took five flights on
average, while only one out of 20.5 Chinese took even one flight,
leaving much room for business, he explained.
</P>
<P>
Yan also gave many reasons for the booming of aviation industry.
The sustained growth of China's national economy, the coming
direct air traffic across the Taiwan Straits, and the development
of western China will all give a boost to the aviation industry.
</P>
<P>
In addition, more and more Chinese are turning to air travel
thanks to their constantly improving living standards. China is
also expecting more international air traffic as it seeks entry to
the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
Yan noted that China will remain a huge market for aircraft as
its air transport keeps expanding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
