<DOCNO> XIE20000417.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Medical Ethics Should Not Be Neglected: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Rapid progress in medical
technology has triggered many ethical problems which should not be
neglected, according to a Chinese health official.
</P>
<P>
Although high technology has led to more advanced treatment,
many problems also appear to be unavoidable, such as rocketing
medical expenses, regional imbalance in health-care resources, and
euthanasia, said Zhu Zonghan, director of the Beijing Municipal
Bureau of Health.
</P>
<P>
Nowadays, many patients must forego effective but unaffordable
drugs, while new technology and highly skilled personnel are often
concentrated in the major hospitals of big cities, leaving the
majority of basic health care facilities in urban communities and
rural areas without these medical advances.
</P>
<P>
"Under such circumstances, principles of humanitarianism and
fairness are often challenged," Zhu was quoted in today's
Guangming Daily.
</P>
<P>
As modern technology can help maintain the life of a severely
ill patient, often at heavy cost, the necessity for euthanasia, as
well as the value of life, should be considered seriously, he said.
</P>
<P>
Another problem associated with medical progress is that
doctors may increasingly rely on technology while paying less
attention to the psychological condition of their patients, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"If we do not attach importance to the negative impact of
medical development and related social problems, overall social
progress could be affected," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000417.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Website on White-Flag Dolphin Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- China has just opened a website
providing information concerning research and protection of the
white-flag dolphin in China, one of the 12 most endangered animal
species in the world.
</P>
<P>
The website, which can be reached at www.ibaiji.org, was
launched last week by the Wuhan Institute of Hydrobiology under
the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) in Wuhan, capital of central
China's Hubei Province as part of the efforts to save the animal
by improving the public awareness of the situation facing the
animal.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Xianfeng, a white-flag dolphin expert with the institute,
said the large mammal, which can only be found in the middle and
lower reaches of the Yangtze River, is a much more endangered
animal than the giant panda.
</P>
<P>
The dwindling number of the dolphin, which has existed for 20
to 30 million years, totals only about 100, or one-third than the
1986 figure, and one tenth of that the giant panda.
</P>
<P>
Both the dolphin and the giant panda are described by
scientists as living fossil and receive top-level state protection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000417.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Who Earns More Money in China: Survey (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Career, education, and age are
the most important factors deciding the income of Chinese people,
according to a recent survey by the National Bureau of Statistic.
</P>
<P>
The survey reveals that people involved in high-tech industries,
real estate, finance, and insurance had the highest incomes in
1999, while people from the service sector and the machinery and
mining industries earned the least amount of money.
</P>
<P>
Experts predict that this income distribution profile will
continue for the next few years.
</P>
<P>
People in the highest income bracket earn more than 200,000
yuan (about 24,000 US dollars) a year, but they account for less
than one percent of the Chinese population, which now stands at 1.
25 billion.
</P>
<P>
The survey also shows that the higher the education level, the
higher the income.
</P>
<P>
Some people around the age of 30 are now making a fortune, a
prospect undreamed of by the older generation now in their 60s and
70s.
</P>
<P>
The survey indicates that the average per-capita income of
families with breadwinners below the age of 30 is much higher than
those of families with primary earners of 41 to 45.
</P>
<P>
This is because young people are usually better educated and
have fewer family burdens, and they are also more willing to get
involved in the new industries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000417.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annette Lu's Separatist Remarks Refuted in Macao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Over the past several days
newspapers and scholars in Macao have strongly refuted the remarks
of Annette Lu advocating "independence of Taiwan".
</P>
<P>
The Macao Daily News said in an editorial on Saturday that "
there would be no peaceful days in the country without the
eradication of those advocating Taiwan independence."
</P>
<P>
Annette Lu's absurd statements of "distant relatives and close
neighbors" obliterated the history that Taiwan has been an
inalienable part of China's territory, and distorted the flesh-and-
blood ties of the people across the Taiwan Straits, the editorial
said.
</P>
<P>
Other local newspapers also noted that Annette Lu has
stubbornly advocated "independence of Taiwan", and seems to walk
farther along the notorious path, challenging all the Chinese
people who are resolved to complete the reunification of the
motherland.
</P>
<P>
Vong Fong Va, director of the Macao Chinese Education
Association, said in an interview with Xinhua on Saturday that
Annette Lu is merely driven by her political ambition and that her
statements are more cheeky than the separatist remarks of Lee Teng-
hui.
</P>
<P>
"She is making a bet on the security of the 23 million people
in Taiwan," Vong Fong Va said, warning that Taiwan people should
be highly alert to her actions.
</P>
<P>
Ieong Wan Chong, a professor with the University of Macao, also
in an interview with Xinhua, said that reunification of the two
sides of the Taiwan Straits is a major trend and the common
aspiration of the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
"The clamors of Annette Lu are only the last struggles of those
advocating Taiwan independence and her actions are doomed to fail,
" the scholar said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
