<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Turkish Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Turkish newspapers on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Daily News:
</P>
<P>
-- Turkey on Sunday asked the British government, for the second
time in two days, to tighten security to protect Turkish nationals
and their property in the country on the eve of the soccer match
between Turkey's Galatasaray team and Britain's Leeds United on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Turks who live in Britain continued to be attacked in revenge
after two British soccer fans were stabbed to death by Turkish
hooligans during Galatasaray-Leeds United match in Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
Milliyet (National):
</P>
<P>
-- The leaders of Turkey's ruling coalition were expected to
hold a summit again on Monday to determine a candidate for the
presidential post.
</P>
<P>
The summit, held in last Thursday, did not reach any consensus
on a candidate. The poll showed that people expect a new president
to be corruption-free, honest and democratic.
</P>
<P>
Hurriyet (Freedom):
</P>
<P>
-- A trade delegation consisting of Turkish businessmen will
visit Iran between May 27-31 to explore ways of expanding bilateral
trade in the fields of iron, chemical, plastic, automotive,
packaging, food, glass, textile and electronic goods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
