<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- The police Sunday recommended indicting Israeli
Transportation Minister Yitzhak Mordechai on three counts of
committing indecent acts by force against three women over an
eight-year period. The crimes carry a total maximum sentence of
seven years in jail.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the police recommended indicting Michal Kallah,
head of the Transportation Ministry bureau in Tel Aviv, and
Mordechai's driver Meir Ohayun for obstruction of justice. The
police handed over their recommendations to the State Attorney's
Office for review.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai issued a statement claiming he is innocent of all the
charges and "would fight with all my might to prove my innocence
and to preserve my good name."
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak is considering handing over
more than 1 percent of the West Bank as part of a third
redeployment that would be linked to the framework agreement he
wants to reach with the Palestinians by mid-May.
</P>
<P>
While the Palestinians are expecting a major handover of
territory in the third redeployment, possibly as much as all of the
territory of the West Bank except specific parcels of land where
there are settlements and military installations, Israel believes
it is only bound to hand over 1 percent by agreements with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
In Sunday's cabinet session, Barak said he was considering
integrating part of the third withdrawal into the framework
agreement. He did not mention any specific numbers.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- The release of the 13 Lebanese administrative detainees,
ordered by the Israeli Supreme Court last week, will not be carried
out Monday as scheduled, following a last-minute appeal by the
family of missing Israeli navigator Ron Arad, who was captured in
Lebanon in 1986.
</P>
<P>
The detainees have been imprisoned for years without trial as
bargaining chips to be used in exchange for information on Israel
Defense Forces soldiers taken prisoners or missing in action in
Lebanon. Several of them were imprisoned without trial for 13
years.
</P>
<P>
The Prison Authority had nearly completed its preparations for
freeing the detainees, who were originally expected to be released
Monday to the Red Cross in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- To no one's surprise, the 25-percent plunge in New York's
Nasdaq index in the past week began to take its toll on Tel Aviv
Sunday. And like Nasdaq, high-tech stocks were especially hard-hit
with the Tel-tech index losing 17 percent of its value.
</P>
<P>
The bull-chip Maof index fell 7.4 percent to 464.8 points and
the Tel Aviv 100 slipped 8.1 percent to 460.5 points. Market
traders could not recall such steep losses in a single day since
1994.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attributed some of the decline to the coming halt in
trade for the Jewish Passover holiday. It is still unclear whether
the trend would lead to further sell-offs at the start of trading
Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
