<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Namibia Relaxes Exchange Controls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Namibia has
relaxed its exchange controls, the South African Business Day
newspaper reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
In terms of the new policy, Namibian companies are allowed to
invest up to 38.5 million U.S. dollars in member countries of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) and up to 7.7
million dollars elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
To encourage investments, companies will now be allowed to use
 part of their local cash holdings to finance up to 10 percent of
approved new foreign investments.
</P>
<P>
Companies may also make use of asset-share swaps to finance
their investments abroad. They will now be allowed to utilize part
of their local cash holdings to repay up to 10 percent of their
outstanding foreign debt raised to finance foreign investments,
provided the foreign debt has been in existence for a minimum
period of two years.
</P>
<P>
For institutional investors, the current asset swap
dispensation will remain, but the 15 percent limit of "total
assets employed in Namibia" will change to "15 percent of total
assets".
</P>
<P>
For unit trusts, the definition will be the same for
institutional investors, but the limit will be increased to 20
percent of "total assets under management".
</P>
<P>
Further, long-term insurers, pension funds and unit trusts,
through unit trust management companies, may now apply to avail of
foreign currency transfers in this year of up to 10 percent of the
net inflow of funds during the 1999 calendar year, to acquire
foreign portfolio investments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000417.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaria Kills 99 in Southwest Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Malaria has claimed 99 lives in
the past three months in southwest Kenya, the Daily Nation
newspaper reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Julius Ogato, medical superintendent of the
Kisii General Hospital in Nyanza Province, as saying that in the
period there were 2,030 patients admitted to the hospital and
diagnosed with malaria fever.
</P>
<P>
The month of January had the highest number of fatalities, 38,
followed by February with 34 and March with 27, Ogato said.
</P>
<P>
He said malaria cases are expected to rise following the
arrival of the long rains, but his hospital has enough drugs to
last for two weeks with another consignment expected to arrive
from the capital Nairobi soon.
</P>
<P>
Local leaders in Kisii, a malaria-prone area along the Lake
Victoria, have been urged to sensitize the people to preventive
measures against the disease to avoid epidemics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
