<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, April 17 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- A U.S. company is developing Atlantic salmon that
can grow up to 10 times faster than normal and, at 18 months old,
are five times the size of their natural counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Massachusetts-based AF Protein, which is carrying out its
research on Prince Edward Island, expects these new super-fish to
be cleared for consumer consumption within a year.
</P>
<P>
If given the green light, these fish would be the first
genetically modified (GM) animal to hit the market. The technology
could drastically change the way fish are farmed since the
technique cuts the cost of raising certain species such as salmon
and trout in half. (US-Gene)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- Eight people were killed and over 30 others were
wounded in a grenade blast in a busy intersection in Baclaran,
Metro Manila, Sunday afternoon, according to a local ABS-CBN
television report Monday.
</P>
<P>
It said that the explosion occurred as thousands of people were
attending Palm Sunday mass at the nearby Redemptorist Church. (
Philippine-Blast)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Russia's President-elect Vladimir Putin is to meet
with British Prime Minister Tony Blair Monday to discuss Russia's
economy, relations with Europe and developments in the rebel
region of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
During his 24-hour visit, Putin will meet Queen Elizabeth II
and hold talks with British businessmen to urge them to invest in
Russia, which he says now becomes more stable and predictable. (
Russia-Britain-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ALMA-ATA -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright held
talks with Kyrgyz President Askar Akayev Sunday and promised U.S.
aid to help Kyrgyzstan combat drug trafficking, arms smuggling and
international terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Under the aid package announced by Albright, the United States
will provide about 3 million U.S. dollars to help train and equip
Kyrgyz border guards, customs and security services, said the
Kyrgyz news agency. (US-Kyrgyzstan-Aid)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Attacks by ethnic Albanian extremists on non-ethnic
Albanian residents have been escalating under the connivance of
the U.N. peacekeeping force in Kosovo, the Yugoslav News Agency
Tanjug said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, some ethnic Albanians burnt down 250 Serbian
houses in a village in Pechi and the last two Serbian houses left
in Urosevac region. Serbian residents have fled their hometown for
fear of terrorist attacks by ethnic Albanians since the
peacekeeping force entered Kosovo last June, Tanjug said. (
Yugoslavia-Kosovo) 
</P>
</TEXT>
