<HEADLINE> Coca-Cola Establishes Bottling Group with COFCO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to an agreement signed last Friday, Coca-Cola and
COFCO will jointly set up the Hong Kong-based COFCO Coca-Cola Co.,
Ltd. to explore the soft drink market in China.
</P>
<P>
The new company, which will oversee bottling factories in south
China's Hainan Province and north China's Tianjin Municipality,
will become a major partner of Coca-Cola in China, according to
the Coca-Cola Co..
</P>
<P>
The COFCO, one of the country's largest foreign trade firms,
has cooperated with Coca-Cola for more than 20 years, and has
invested in 12 of Coca-Cola's bottling factories in China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000417.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's External Reserves Remains Robust </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's external reserves
remained robust, Finance Minister Tun Daim Zainuddin said Monday.
</P>
<P>
As at March 31 this year, the country's reserves stood at 33.9
billion U.S.dollars, sufficient to finance 6.3 months of retained
imports, he said at Kuala Lumpur City Securities Sdn Bhd "
Conference for Fund Managers," in Putra Jaya near here.
</P>
<P>
"This exceeded the minimum target of five months set under the
National Economic Recovery Plan. At this level, our external
reserves are 5.7 times higher than our short term external debt,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's debt servicing ratio remained low at 5.3 percent,
the minister said, adding his country's credit standing continued
to remain strong while the risk of default never arose, even at
the height of the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Tun Daim Zainuddin also said the 5.8 percent gross domestic
product (GDP) growth projected for this year would emanate mainly
from the pick up in domestic demand in general, the stronger
private consumption in particular.
</P>
<P>
Private capital expenditure is expected to strengthen and
register positive growth as excess production capacity diminishes
with higher output while public sector fixed capital formation is
expected to continue to increase at a double digit rate, he said.
</P>
<P>
With the pick up in demand in the country this year, there
would be some build-up in inflationary pressures but the rate is
not expected to exceed three percent, according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
He said that his country's economic outlook is very positive,
barring any unforeseen adverse developments on the international
front.
</P>
<P>
The foundation of Malaysia's future economic growth has been
strengthened following the recovery measures that had been
implemented, the minister said, stressing that Malaysia remains
committed to ensuring that the reforms it has put in place would
continue to further strengthen the economy and the financial
system.
</P>
<P>
The two-day fund managers'conference was attended by some 30
local and foreign fund managers including those from Salomon Smith
Barney, Brunei Investment Agency and Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
