<DOCNO> XIE20000417.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Sets Up New Refuge for Black Robin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Pitt Island in the Chatham
Islands, which is 800 kilometers from New Zealand's east coast,
was designated Monday as a new refuge for the black robin, one of
the world's rarest birds.
</P>
<P>
According to an announcement from the New Zealand Department of
Conservation (DOC), the numbers of black robins have increased
from a low of only five birds in 1979 to a current population of
more than 250. Although New Zealand already has two island
reserves for the black robin, the increase of its population has
prompted DOC to set up a new sanctuary on Pitt Island.
</P>
<P>
Hillary Aikman, a DOC official, said that work has begun on a
fence to keep out pests and DOC should be able to transfer black
robins there next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
