<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Plunge in Tokyo, Nikkei Slips Below 19,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Share prices nose-dived across the
board in Tokyo Monday morning, dampened by last Friday's plunge on
the Wall Street, with the key Nikkei index briefly losing more
than 1,800 points.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange declined 1,750.79 points, or 8.
57 percent, to end the morning session at 18,683.89.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, tumbled 130.53 points or 7.89 percent to 1,
523.17.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section increased to 474.12 million
shares from last Friday morning's 396.02 million shares.
</P>
<P>
High-priced telecommunication issues faced selling while
exporters were lower, reflecting the weakness on the Wall Street
and the yen's rise.
</P>
<P>
The worst performer was the brokerage industry, falling 14.64
percent.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors, the major driving force in the Tokyo stock
market, were net sellers.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers overwhelmed
gainers 1,233 to 49, with 36 issues unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The plunge in the stock market prompted a senior official of
Japan's ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) to announce
emergency measures to cope with the situation.
</P>
<P>
"As emergency measures, the LDP wants to prop up the stock
market with such steps as an injection of public funds. I am
thinking of an injection of at least one trillion yen (about 9.6
billion U.S. dollars) in public funds," Shizuka Kamei, chairman of
the LDP's Policy Research Council, told reporters early in the day.
</P>
</TEXT>
