<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Remittance by Expatriate S.Lankan Workers Up 23 Pct in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Expatriate Sri Lankan workers
remitted 74 billion rupees (1,056 million U.S. dollars) in 1999, a
23 percent increase in rupee terms over the previous year, the
official Daily News reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Some 60 percent of this remittance was sent in by housemaids,
Foreign Employment Bureau officials were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
There are some 1.2 million Sri Lankans working abroad, mostly
in Middle East countries, as housemaids.
</P>
<P>
Expatriate workers represented a major source of foreign income
for the country and accordingly all efforts were made to find
foreign employment for Sri Lankans, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report said there are lucrative employment opportunities
for Sri Lankans in Cyprus, Singapore, Malaysia and China's Hong
Kong. The salaries paid in these countries and regions were better
than those paid in Middle East countries, where the decline in
wages was attributed to an influx of housemaids from other Asian
countries.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Employment Bureau is now encouraging male workers
to seek employment abroad as many problems in society is traced to
the absence of housewives in households here.
</P>
<P>
There has been an increasing demand for skilled workers such as
welders, painters, electricians and plumbers in Middle East
countries,the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
