<DOCNO> XIE20000417.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Be Flooded With Drug Pills: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Up to 400 million methamphetamine
pills are expected to end up on the streets in Thailand this year,
despite the best efforts of suppression agencies, the Bangkok Post
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Quoting a report of the Thai Farmers Research Center, the
report said widespread acceptance of the drug by laborers and
their families, who viewed it as a means of overcoming fatigue,
working longer and boosting income, is a major problem.
</P>
<P>
Estimated illegal sales could reach 50 billion baht (1.33
billion U.S. dollars), the center reported. When medical costs and
other programs were included, the total cost to society would be
more than 100 billion baht (2.66 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The report said the Thai government was finding it hard to
suppress methamphetamine because of the ease of its production,
high demand and profitability.
</P>
<P>
A survey of 728 laborers in Bangkok recently found many were
addicted to methamphetamine and viewed the drug only as a
stimulant, not a narcotic, and about 89 percent of the respondents
said they needed a stimulant to work hard without feeling
exhausted.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, their families considered their drug abuse as an act
of devotion to income-earning, thus boosting the popularity of
methamphetamine among laborers.
</P>
<P>
The center estimated the customer base of methamphetamine among
laborers in Bangkok at 200,000-300,000 people, making the capital
a major market worth hundreds of millions of baht in annual sales.
</P>
<P>
It suggested the government not only tackle the supply of
methamphetamine by arresting traffickers but also try to reduce
demand through education and make greater efforts to rehabilitate
addicts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000417.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Accuses Ethnic Albanians of Attacking Serbians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Attacks by ethnic Albanian
extremists on non-ethnic Albanian residents have been escalating
under the connivance of the U.N. peacekeeping force in Kosovo, the
Yugoslav News Agency Tanjug said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, some ethnic Albanians burnt down 250 Serbian
houses in a village in Pechi and the last two Serbian houses left
in Urosevac region. Serbian residents have fled their hometown
for fear of terrorist attacks by ethnic Albanians since the
peacekeeping force entered Kosovo last June, Tanjug said.
</P>
<P>
Before the houses were set on fire, ethnic Albanian extremists
loaded 15 trucks with electrical appliances and furniture robbed
from those houses. Local observers said the attacks aimed to
prevent Serbians from returning to their hometown.
</P>
<P>
The news agency condemned the peacekeeping force for turning a
blind eye on the violence and did not take any action to stop it.
</P>
<P>
According to Yugoslav official statistics, there have been 4,
360 attacks in Kosovo since last June, leaving nearly 1,000 people
dead and 50,000 houses burnt down, and forcing 360,000 non-ethnic
Albanians to flee their homes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
