<HEADLINE> Indonesian Consumers Upbeat Over Economic Outlook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian consumers have
confidence that the country's economy is on the rise and the
economic conditions will improve over the next six months, a local
newspapers reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
For the first time since October 1999, the percentage of
consumers claiming current conditions were good outweighed the
percentage claiming otherwise, the Jakarta Post daily Monday
reported quoting the findings of the country's survey institute,
the Danareksa Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
It said that consumers remained upbeat on the economic outlook
despite domestic social and political uncertainties.
</P>
<P>
"The positive expectations typically point to the active pace
of economic recovery underway and underline the characteristics of
an economy that is at the incipient stage of a business cycle
upswing,"the Institute said.
</P>
<P>
Although the majority still believed jobs were difficult to
find,the proportions of optimistic responses was increasing
compared with the February survey.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has been under the intensive care of the
International Monetary Fund after the economy was hit by the
economic crisis that started in the middle of 1997.
</P>
<P>
But there are signs that the economy is improving. Bank
Indonesia expressed confidence last week that the 3 percent to 4
percent gross domestic growth and "underline" inflation of 3
percent to 5 percent target of this year could be attained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
