<HEADLINE> Qinghai to Boost Plateau Tourism by Building New Highways </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Qinghai Province
has decided to build five new highways to boost its plateau
tourism amid a national drive to develop western areas.
</P>
<P>
According to local communication department, the total
investment for the five highways will be 580 million yuan ( 69.8
million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The five big projects include a 161-kilometer highway circling
Qinghai Lake, the largest inland saltwater lake in the country and
a 60-kilometer highway inside a national-level forest park.
</P>
<P>
With its unique highland landscape, multi-ethnic custom and
rare birds, Qinghai province has attracted flocks of domestic and
overseas visitors every year.
</P>
<P>
But underdeveloped highway construction cannot meet the demand
of the rapidly growing tourism, local communication officials said.
</P>
<P>
To grasp the opportunity of an ongoing national campaign to
develop western China, Qinghai communication department mapped out
the plan to build the highways, the officials added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
