<HEADLINE> Myanmar Generates 4.3 Bln Kwh of Electricity in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Electric power generated by the
state-run Myanma Electric Power Enterprise (MEPE) totaled 4.309
billion kilowatt-hours (kwh) in 1999, according to the latest
figures released by the country's Central Statistical Organization.
</P>
<P>
The installed generating capacity (IGC) of the MEPE, the main
electricity supplier of the country, was 1,058 megawatts (mw) at
the end of December 1999, it said.
</P>
<P>
In the past 11 years, Myanmar's IGC increased by 509 mw. Of the
figure, the IGC of natural gas rose by 255 mw, steam power by 143
mw and hydropower by 111 mw.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is now building five hydro-electric power plants. Of
them, three are being built by China. These five power plants,
upon completion, will add 407 mw to Myanmar's IGC and will greatly
ease the serious electricity shortage in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
