<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Law to Protect Rights of Patients </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- A public health official said the
Chinese government would do more to help the estimated 15 million
Chinese suffering from mental illness, including drafting a law to
protect their rights and increasing public awareness to end the
discrimination and marginalization faced by patients.
</P>
<P>
"Mental illness is now such a serious problem that we have to
face it whether we want to or not," Yin Dakui, vice-minister of
health was quoted by China Daily as saying.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks last week at a special auction held to sell
artwork by patients suffering from mental illness to raise fund
for their treatment.
</P>
<P>
Yin said the government is now carrying out a publicity
campaign to improve people's awareness of mental illness.
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese people are often unwilling to admit that
they or their relatives have mental disorders until suicides are
committed.
</P>
<P>
"Discrimination against mental patients is so wide-spread it
has become the biggest obstacle to treating mental illness," he
said.
</P>
<P>
According to the law being drafted, employers cannot fire
employees just because they have mental diseases, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
