<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Efforts Urged to Improve Environment in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Environmentalists have called for
more afforestation efforts in the wake of the dust and sand storms
that hit Beijing, Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region, Shaanxi
Province, and other parts of north China this spring.
</P>
<P>
Low vegetation coverage rate is to blame for the dust and sand
storms, according to meteorologists, and the forest coverage is
less than one percent in some areas in north China.
</P>
<P>
Air quality in northwest China and north China deteriorated
during the sand and dust storms, which even affected Qingdao, a
beautiful coastal city in east China's Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
The China Environment Monitoring Station reported that the
intensity of dust particles in the air in Beijing, Taiyuan,
Lanzhou and Hohhot increased recently.
</P>
<P>
Meteorologists said the dust and sand storms were brought about
by strong cold air that visited north China, where there had been
little rainfall this spring. Other factors included higher
temperature in early spring and softened earth.
</P>
<P>
Being aware of the urgency of improving the environment, the
Chinese government has decided to build forest shelter belts on a
large scale in northwest China while accelerating the development
of the western part of the country. Farmers have been encouraged
to plant more trees by retiring fragile farmland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
