<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Trade-Related News (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of major trade-related
news in the past week ( April 10-16) are as follows:
</P>
<P>
Import and Export
</P>
<P>
-- China's imports maintained the growth momentum in March in
spite of a decline of growth rate after the vigorous surge in the
previous two months this year, according to customs figures
released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Imports in March rose 24 percent over that of the same month
last year, but the growth rate fell far from the average 54
percent in January and February. The growth rate for the first
three months stood at 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
-- China's foreign trade in the first quarter this year topped
98.2 billion U.S. dollars, representing an impressive 40-percent
growth rate from a year earlier, and raking in a trade surplus of
5.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Exports in the first three months hit 51.7 billion U.S. dollars,
up 39 percent year on year, and imports reached 46.5 billion
dollars, up 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
China's imports in the first three months this year rose by 39
percent over the same period last year, registering the highest
growth rate since the second quarter of 1995.
</P>
<P>
-- A total of 4,316 foreign-funded enterprises were authorized
during the first quarter, rising 22.5 percent from the same period
last year. Total contractual foreign investment reached 11.08
billion U.S. dollars, up 27 percent year-on-year, with paid-in
foreign capital dropping 2.72 percent to 7.14 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
-- Customs officers in east China's Jiangsu Province have
reported the appearance of harmful pine worms in the wood packing
of three batches of imported goods from Japan and two batches of
imported goods from the United States.
</P>
<P>
-- China's motorcycles sector exported 60,000 motorcycles in
February alone, up 372 percent over the same month last year,
earning 30.62 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
-- Twenty-eight economic and management officials from 15
French-speaking African countries gathered in the Chinese capital
last Tuesday for the opening ceremony of the Fourth China-Africa
Seminar for Economic and Management Officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
