<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Trade-Related News (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- Taiwan's investment in the mainland has kept a strong
momentum for the first three months this year, according to
Assistant Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation Ma
Xiuhong.
</P>
<P>
The number of newly-authorized foreign-funded enterprises for
the first quarter rose by 13 percent over the same period last
year, and the contractual value went up 46 percent.
</P>
<P>
-- Taiwan's accumulated investment in Xiamen, a coastal city in
east China, has taken up approximately one-tenth of its total
investment in the mainland, Xiamen's vice-mayor Su Shuli said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Su said that Xiamen has to date seen over 1,700 Taiwan-invested
enterprises established in the city, with contractual Taiwan
investment of 3.5 billion U.S. dollars and paid-in capital of
three billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
-- China's policy for encouraging foreign investment in the
western part of the country, formulated last fall, is now being
carried out in a comprehensive way, Ma Xiuhong said.
</P>
<P>
Ma said that seven provincial capitals in the west have
already received the go-ahead to set up state-level development
zones, while another seven are still waiting for authorization.
The catalog of industries in the west that enjoy comparative
advantages has been finished and is waiting to be released, she
added.
</P>
<P>
-- The number of overseas-funded real estate enterprises has
exceeded 5,000, accounting for 20 percent of the country's total,
said the Ministry of Construction.
</P>
<P>
Among the overseas-funded real estate enterprises, 3,800 are
from Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan investors.
</P>
<P>
China plans to build 1.5 billion square meters of urban housing
and 2.9 billion square meters of rural housing by 2005, creating a
huge market for overseas investors, said the ministry.
</P>
