<HEADLINE> Syrian, Canadian PMs Hold talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Prime Minister Mohammed
Mustafa Miro held talks with his visiting Canadian counterpart Jean
Chretien Monday, but no details of the discussion were disclosed.
</P>
<P>
The official Syrian Arab News Agency (SANA) quoted Canadian
Ambassador Alexandra Bugailiskis as saying that Chretien's two-day
visit to Syria is to boost bilateral ties and sound out Syrian
government's views on the peace process with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Syrian-Israeli peace talks that resumed last December after a
45-month hiatus hit a snag again in January due to Israel's refusal
to commit itself to full withdrawal from the Golan Heights it
seized from Syria in the 1967 Mideast War.
</P>
<P>
Canada prefers to remain neutral and help both sides arrive at
acceptable solutions, the ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
Syria is part of Chretien's regional tour, which has taken him
to Jordan, Israel, the Palestinian territories, Egypt and Lebanon,
and he will travel on to Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Chretien is also expected to meet with Syrian President Hafez
al-Assad.
</P>
<P>
A Canadian contingent of 180 troops serves in the U.N. observer
force on the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
Canada also chairs the refugee committee for the regional
multilateral peace process talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
