<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2100GMT, Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Five Israelis were found guilty in the case of the
bridge collapse disaster in Israel during the Maccabiah Games in
1997, an Israeli court announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
The five, who played key organizational roles in the games,
should be responsible for their negligence which caused deaths and
injuries, said Tel Aviv Magistrate's Court. The defendants are
facing a maximum prison term of four years.
</P>
<P>
The tragedy took place on the occasion of the opening ceremony
of the 15th Maccabiah Games, the Jewish Olympics, on July 14, 1997,
in which four Australian Jewish athletes were killed and nearly 70
injured. (Israel-Maccabiah Disaster)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ALEXANDRIA (Egypt)-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin met here
Monday with his Egyptian counterpart Hosni Mubarak and exchanged
views on bilateral relations and issues of mutual interest.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak welcomed and thanked Jiang for coming to Alexandria for
the meeting at his invitation.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, who had visited China seven times, said he treasures
the relations with China, and expressed hope to visit China again
in the future.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said he was very glad to meet Mubarak again, one year
after their last meeting in China. He thanked Mubarak for inviting
him to Egypt and meeting with him in the world famous historic city
of Alexandria.(Egypt-China-Jiang-Mubarak)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak will convene a
special cabinet session on Tuesday to discuss the way to block the
release of 13 Lebanese administrative detainees now in custody in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was issued Monday afternoon by Barak's office
after Israel's Supreme Court rejected the appeal against the
release earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
The ruling once seemed to clear the way for the transfer of
these detainees to the International Red Cross organization in
south Lebanon, which was originally due to take place on Monday.
</P>
<P>
But now there will be no new date set for the release before the
cabinet session. (Israel-Lebanese Detainees)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GAZA -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat asserted here Monday
that his upcoming summit meeting with U.S. President Bill Clinton
in Washington is a "substantial and basic point" in pushing forward
the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat made the remarks following his meeting with visiting
Omani Minister of State for Foreign Affairs Yousef Bin Alawi Bin
Abdullah.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and Clinton are due to meet in Washington on April 20 in
an effort to advance the ongoing Israeli-Palestinian talks at the
Bolling Air Base near Washington.
</P>
<P>
The two sides are striving hard to draft a framework agreement
by May for a final peace treaty by September.  (Palestine-
Arafat-Washington Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUSM -- Syrian Third Vice President Mohammed Zouhair
Musharaqah vowed Monday that his country would never give up any
inch of its territories or compromise its rights and sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
The vow was made during the celebrations held by the Damascus
Committee of the ruling Arab Socialist Baathist Party at the
Damascus University to mark the 54th anniversary of Syrian
Liberation.
</P>
<P>
On April 17, 1946, the last soldier of the French occupation
forces left Syria, marking Syria's independence from French
colonial rule. (Syria-Vice President-Territories) 
</P>
