<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek FM Willing to Meet Turkish Cypriot Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Greek Foreign Minister George
Papandreou has expressed his willingness to meet with Turkish
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash, the Macedonian Press Agency (MPA)
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Denktash said recently that he intended to meet with
Papandreou, who said that he would gladly meet with Denktash when
they, as European citizens, would be able to cross Cyprus from end
to end, without technical or other obstacles.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriots-controlled
south and the Turkish Cypriots-dominated north since 1974 when
Turkey invaded and occupied the northern third of the island in
the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
Greece, a major supporter of the Cyprus Republic-led Galfcos
Clerides, has insisted that the Cyprus issue must be resolved on
the basis of the establishment of a bizonal, bicommunal federation
in line with U.N. resolutions, but Turkey and the Turkish Cypriot
side demand that northern Cyprus, illegally declared in 1983, be
recognized internationally as a prelude to reunification in the
form of a two-state confederation.
</P>
<P>
In Athens, the two-day low-level policy talks between Greek
and Turkish foreign ministry officials got underway Monday. Both
sides are focusing on bilateral cooperation in the European Union
(EU) program.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the recent rapprochement between Athens
and Ankara will help resolve the protracted Cyprus issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
