<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hughes Authorized to Launch Canada's Anik F2 Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Telesat Canada has authorized
Hughes Space &AMP; Communications International to build its Anik F2
communications satellite, the Ottawa-based satellite operator
announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
Anik F2, which is estimated to cost 600 million Canadian
dollars (about 408 million U.S. dollars), "will be the most
advanced satellite Telesat has ever launched," said Larry Boisvert,
president of Telesat Canada.
</P>
<P>
"As the newest in Telesat's fleet of satellites, Anik F2 will
provide valuable capacity for North American customers with
telecommunications, broadcasting and multimedia needs," he said.
</P>
<P>
Anik F2, to be launched in late 2002, will carry a Ka-band high-
speed, multimedia communications payload worth 109 million
Canadian dollars (about 74 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The highly advanced communications satellite will also include
C-band and Ku-band payloads to replace the existing capacity on
the Anik E satellites when they reach the end of their service
lives.
</P>
<P>
Hughes is the manufacturer of Telesat's Anik F1 satellite,
which will go into space late this summer, according to the
Canadian satellite company. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
