<HEADLINE> Mexico's Popocatepetl Volcano Lets Out Ashes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Volcano Popocateptl, 75
kilometers east of Mexico's capital, let forth Monday a cloud of
ashes that reached a height of 2,000 meters, said Monday official
sources.
</P>
<P>
This precipitation of ashes didn't cause damages, nor did this
volcano's new activity represent eventual danger for inhabitants
of neighboring areas, said Servando De La Cruz, an expert from
National Disaster Prevention Center (Cenapred).
</P>
<P>
De la Cruz disagreed with the theory that the letting out of
ashes is associated with an increase of the eruptive phase of this
volcano of 5,450 meters, situated in Puebla state.
</P>
<P>
According to this expert, the expulsion of ashes corresponds to
the destruction of a lava dome formed last February 26 inside the
volcano. Cenapred, under Secretariat of Government, is keeping a
yellow alert regarding the volcano. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
