<DOCNO> XIE20000417.0371 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Unveils Efficient Hybrid Fuel Cell Turbine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The new device combines a fuel cell, which creates electricity
directly from natural gas, with a gas turbine that uses the hot
exhaust from the fuel cell to generate a second stream of
electricity.
</P>
<P>
The device represents the first mating of a fuel cell with a
gas turbine. It will generate power at 55 percent efficiency, 5
percent higher than the current generation of gas-fired power
plants. Its efficiency could exceed 70 percent with more
development.
</P>
<P>
The new power plant is capable of generating 220 kilowatts of
power, enough for more than 200 homes, according to the DOE.
</P>
<P>
Because no combustion occurs in the fuel cell, which creates
electricity by chemically breaking down the natural-gas fuel, the
pollution levels are drastically reduced.
</P>
<P>
The device produces no sulfur dioxide. Its output of nitrogen
oxide, which can turn into urban smog, will be 50 times as low as
current gas-fired power plants. And its emissions of carbon
dioxide, which is thought to be artificially warning the Earth's
atmosphere, will be reduced by 75 percent, said the DOE.
</P>
<P>
The power plant was developed by Siemens Westinghouse Inc., a
unit of Siemens AG, and will be tested for a year by Southern
California Edison to see how it performs in a commercial setting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000417.0372 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Ministers, WHO Official Urge International Aid For African Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Two African ministers for
health and a World Health Organization (WHO) official Monday
stressed the need for urgent increased political and financial
commitment by the international community to substantially improve
the health situation in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the United Nations Economic and Social Council, Dr.
Ebrahim M. Samba, the WHO's regional director for Africa, said
that the disease burden in Africa continued to exacerbate the
problem of poverty and called for concerted efforts to break the
vicious cycle of ill-health, poverty and underdevelopment.
</P>
<P>
He welcomed the decision by G-8 in 1999 to introduce a wide-
ranging package of debt relief to developing countries, but noted
that 33 of 41 heavily indebted countries and 29 of the 35
countries with low human development index were in Africa.
</P>
<P>
"The debt burden has re-entrenched the indebted countries
deeper and deeper into the vicious cycle of poverty. We urge
bilateral and multilateral agencies to consider total debt
forgiveness," he said.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Health and Social Services of Namibia and current
Chairperson of the WHO Regional Committee for Africa Dr. Libertine
Amathila underlined the gravity of the health problems facing
African countries and appealed to the advanced countries to come
urgently to their assistance.
</P>
<P>
"The health situation in Africa has been worsened by the AIDS
epidemic. It has reversed some of the gains that were realized in
health development. The debt burden has impoverished many African
countries and made it impossible for them to provide affordable
interventions in an already weak health system," he said.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Health and Social Services of Guinea-Conakry Dr.
Kandjoura Drame called for better understanding of Africa's
problems and more prompt response to them by the developed
countries.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed, "The health situation in Africa has been
aggravated by poverty, conflicts and the large number of refugees,
problems which can only be resolved through good governance,
resolution of conflicts, proper management of resources as well as
internal and external partnerships." 
</P>
</TEXT>
